<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Office of Women's Business Development -- Women Business Facts</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<FONT SIZE=+3>Office of Women's Business Development</FONT>
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<HR>

<h3 align=center>
Fact Sheet<br>
Women-Owned Business in Illinois
</h3>


<h3>ILLINOIS RANKS FIFTH IN THE NATION AS HOME TO WOMEN-OWNED BUSINESSES</h3>

<pre>
  the number of women-owned firms                 336,000+
  employment of women-owned firms                 949,000
  sales and receipts of women-owned firms        $119.6 Billion

</pre>

<strong>Number of Firms:</strong>  Between 1987 and 1996, the number of women-owned firms nearly doubled.  1996 estimates by the National Foundation of Women Business Owners rank Illinois fifth in the nation with nearly 337,000 women-owned firms, a 90 percent increase from 1987.<p>

<strong>Industry Distribution:</strong>  Although 82.3 percent remain concentrated in services, retail trade, and FIRE (finance, insurance, and real estate), Illinois women-owned businesses are diversifying:  percent representation in all but two industries showed an increase from 1987.  Services and retail trade declined.  Chicago boasts more women-owned firms in the construction industry than any other major metropolitan area in the country. <p>

<strong>Employment:</strong>  Employment levels sky-rocketed 112 percent, with women-owned businesses employing 315,615 in 1992  -- up from 149,164 in 1987.  Payroll grew from just over two billion to almost six billion, a 175.8 percent increase.<p>
 
<strong>Sales and Receipts:</strong>  Employer firms still enjoy higher sales. While non-employer firms saw a significant 65.5 percent increase from 1987 to 1992, the sales and receipts of employer firms demonstrated a 154.3 percent gain.  Industry sector matters:  firms located in manufacturing enjoyed the highest sales levels, averaging nearly $1.075 million per company compared to $41,645 per company located in services.  Illinois women-owned businesses overall witnessed an extraordinary 252 percent increase in sales between 1987 and 1992.<p>  

<strong>International Trade:</strong>  Seven percent of Illinois' women-owned firms report international sales.  Nationally, the average is 3 percent.  Export activity has primarily occured in the Canadian and European markets, followed by the Pacific Rim, Mexico, and South America.<p>    

<h3>Sources:</h3>

National Foundation of Women Business Owners, 1996 Facts on Women-Owned Businesses<br>
U.S. Bureau of the Census, Survey of Women-Owned Businesses, 1987 and 1992<br>
Mollie Cole, New Voices, New Leadership: A Survey of Illinois Women Business Owners, IL DCCA<p>


<h3>For more information:  </h3>

Office of Women's Business Development<br>  
IL DCCA<br>
James R. Thompson Center<br>
100 West Randolph Street<br>  
Suite 3-400<br>
Chicago  Illinois  60601<br>    
312/814-8736<br>  
Fax: 312/814/5247<br>    
TDD (for hearing impaired): 800/419-0667<br>
World Wide Web: http://www.ilcommerce.com/<p>

Developed through a partnership between the U.S. Small Business Administration and the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs under cooperative agreement #SB-2M-00097-13.<p>

Small Business Division<br>
Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs<br>
James R. Thompson Center<br>
100 W. Randolph, Suite 3-400<br>
Chicago, Illinois 60601<br>
Voice: 312/814-3557<br>
Fax: 312/814-5247<br>
