<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs</h3>
<center><img src="/dcca/graph/tl.gif" alt="Trade Leader" width=572 height=100></center>

<center><font size=+3>Summer 1996</font></center>
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>

<HR>
<h3><center>The International Business Newsletter for the State of Illinois</center></h3>
<hr>

<h3>Rethinking Our Approach to International Trade: Big Emerging Markets</h3>

During the last decade, Americans have been forced to rethink their approach to international trade. This is because many markets that were formally closed to importing and exporting are now viable markets and "open for business" on an international level.<p>

Big Emerging Markets or "BEMs" are the markets that will account for the overwhelming incremental growth in world imports over the next 20 years.<p>

Looking toward the next century, the engines of economic growth will be found in fewer than a dozen regions of the world. The "BEMs" are:  in Asia-the Chinese Economic Area (China, Hong Kong and Taiwan), South Korea, the Association of Southeast Asian Nations  (ASEAN), initially Indonesia, then expanded to include all the ASEAN economies (Thailand, Singapore, Malaysia, the Philippines, Brunei, and Viet Nam), and India; in Africa - South Africa; in Europe - Poland and Turkey; and in Latin America - Mexico, Brazil and Argentina.<p>

The BEMs are unlike our more tradition trading partners, such as Japan, Great Britain or Germany. There are frequently still barriers to entering these markets, including high tariffs, quotas and protectionist regulatory restrictions. Commercial systems, including full respect for intellectual property rights, are often still developing or lacking altogether. In some of the BEMs, impartial legal systems also are missing. The nature of competition we face in these markets is dramatically different from prior experience.<p>

Still, the BEMs continue to provide overwhelming opportunity for exporters. While the markets of Europe and Japan continue to be top ten trading partners for Illinois firms, current trends demonstrate slower growth in these markets than a good deal of the rest of the world.<p>

<hr>
<h3>Why are Big Emerging Markets so Important to Illinois?</h3>

Illinois exports to many of the Big Emerging Markets have already shown extraordinary growth. For instance, between 1992 and 1993, Illinois exports to China increased 239 percent. China is now Illinois' sixth largest trading partner. In 1995, Illinois exports to Thailand, South Korea, Singapore, and Hong Kong grew an average of 83 percent. Exports to Indonesia and Malaysia grew a whopping 101 percent and 140 percent last year. In fact, exports to almost all of the ASEAN nations exhibited double digit growth.<p>

Illinois exports to Turkey increased 85 percent; exports to Poland increased 36 percent and exports to many countries in Africa increased their imports from Illinois as much as 100 percent.<p>

There is no doubt that these Big Emerging Markets are Illinois' fastest growing markets. BEMs will provide the greatest amount of export opportunity in the near future. Companies that develop an export action plan in accordance with these markets will remain competitive in the long term. A BEM strategy should be part of any company's export strategy and will help Illinois firms to maximize their competitive advantage over the long haul. Now is the time to be considering and scrutinizing these critical regions of the world.<p>

<hr>
<h3>The Economic Stakes</h3>

by Margaret MacLean, Managing Director, International Business Division<p>

Earlier this year, every newspaper in America ran daily stories chronicling the state of America negotiations with Chinese officials concerning illegal trade in pirated compact discs and computer software. Why? Because the issue is central both to the future well-being of hundreds of thousands of American workers and to our prospects in a market of 1.2 billion consumers with a voracious appetite for information products.<p>

Economic stakes in the BEMs are enormous. The ten BEMs as a group are importing about as much merchandise form the U.S. as Japan and the European Union combined. In fact, during the period 1990-2010, the BEMs could account for at least $1 trillion incremental U.S. exports.<p>

<hr>
<h3>1996 Governor's Export Awards</h3>

Lt. Governor Kustra and Director Dennis Whetstone announced the winners of the 1996 Governor's Export Awards at the 2nd annual "Crossing International Borders Conference" held at the Chicago Hilton and Towers on May 16, 1996.  The awards were presented in three categories, New to Export, Continuing Export Excellence, and Export Awareness and Development. In addition, the Community Service Recognition category was added as a new award this year.<p>

Companies were judged on the basis of percentage of export sales of total company sales, percentage of growth in export sales, size of export workforce and distinguishing features regarding international marketing strategies. Organizations were reviewed on the basis of regular educational outreach to the international community.<p>

Four winners in the New to Export category were:<p>
<ul>
<h4>Sabratek Corporation</h4>

located in Niles, develops, produces, and markets technologically-advanced, user-friendly and cost effective medical products and related information systems. Early in the company's development, Sabratek developed a corporate strategy of addressing worldwide healthcare needs after realizing that the global changes taking place in the healthcare market were not exclusively a domestic issue, but rather a global issue. Sabratek's goal is to achieve parity between its domestic and export sales (50/50).<p>

<h4>Total Process Corporation</h4>

located in Red Bud, manufacturers process piping, structural steel, electrical controls, prefabricated piping systems process modules, and complete manufacturing facility pre-assembly. Total Process Corporation pre-assembles much of its orders and sells to many foreign markets where these systems are re-assembled. Total Process sells to the Far East, South America, New Zealand, and Europe. Exports account for close to 80 percent of Total Process Corporation sales.<p>

<h4>Visiontek</h4>

located in Gurnee, manufacturers random access memory modules. In 1994, Visiontek worked with the PIE (Partners in Europe), an organization whose goal it is to have 4-5 American technology manufacturers to represent, to establish offices in Europe in the most cost-effective way possible. Now PIE's office in Brussels, Madrid, Munich, and London are also Visiontek offices. This allows Visiontek to concentrate on manufacturing and product development for Europe, and leave decision on PR, advertising, sales, etc., to their European partners. Visiontek has been listed two consecutive years on Crains' list of five fastest growing privately held companies in Chicago.<p>

<h4>Westell International</h4>

located in Oswego, designs and manufacturers telecommunications equipment.   Established in 1994, Westell INternational was created when a new product technology, ASL, was developed for the U.S. market and caught some interest overseas. Westell has seen exports grow at a phenomenal rate, over 500 percent per year, and anticipates its employee count to grow from 30 employees to 151 employees by 1999.<h4></h4>
</ul>

The five winners in the Continuing Export Excellence category were:<p>
<ul>
<h4>The Chicago Stock Exchange </h4>

(CHX) is a financial and technological services company for the securities industry. CHX is the second largest stock exchange in the U.S. in terms of dollar value of shares traded and is a leading supplier of trading systems and service to the securities and financial services industry worldwide.<p>

<h4>Fluid Management L.P</h4>

of Wheeling, is a manufacturer of manual and automatic fluid dispensers for paint, ink, food, pharmaceutical products, and paint mixers and shakers. Fluid Management exports to 46 countries, with exports sales accounting for more than 25 percent of Illinois sales. Fluid Management has opened sales offices in Canada,  Australia, Brazil, Holland, Sweden, the UK and Greece.<h4></h4>

<h4>FRASCA International</h4>

of Urbana, a manufacturer of flight training simulators for both civil and aviation training, began exporting in 1958. They currently export to over 60 countries and have agents in most of the countries to whom they sell. Exports represent the significant sales sector for Frasca, with over 70 percent of their Illinois sales going to export destinations. Frasca expects the expansion of export sales to continue in the next few years, with any expansion in jobs a direct result of export sales.<p>

<h4>Prince Castle, Inc.</h4>

of Carol Stream, manufactures more than 400 different products used for the preparation and holding of food products for the quick serve/fast food industry. Their products are exported to over 80 different countries. Export sales of Prince Castle products have increased more than 30 percent annually for the last five years. Prince Castle established a European distribution center in 1994 and services a network of distributors worldwide.<p>

<h4>Dickey-john Corporation</h4>

of Auburn, a manufacturer of agricultural control equipment used in testing humidity, application of fertilizers, herbicides and other liquid products, has been exporting since 1971. Dickey-john currently exports to over 60 countries and established a sales and service office in Paris, France in 1976. In the same year, they acquired a sales and service facility in Ontario, Canada to provide service to Canada. Nearly one-quarter of Dickey-john's Illinois sales are exports.<p>
</ul>

The four winners in the category of Export Awareness and Development were:<p>
<ul>
<h4>The Automotive Exporters Council of Chicago</h4>

which is celebrating its 50th year, is an organization consisting of practicing exporters actively engaged in the export sales and overseas distribution of automotive parts, accessories, tools, service equipment, and other products used in the automotive industry. They hold a biannual joint meeting in Chicago with the Overseas Automotive Council (OAC), the international division of the Motor Equipment Association (MEMA) trade association, as well as meetings addressing current topics of interest to automotive exporters, such as banking, exchange rates and trade fairs. The Automotive Exporters Council members represent a commitment to state-of-the-art technology, quality and service, and will continue to keep Illinois-made products in demand worldwide.<p>

<h4>The National Housewares Manufacturers Association </h4>

(NHMA) in Rosemont, which was established in 1939 and consists of 321 members, is the premier not-for-profit trade association serving the housewares industry through global information services, trade shows and other marketing interchanges, industry advocacy, trade credit services and group cooperative buying. The NHMA has taken matchmaker missions and participated in trade shows in Europe, Eastern Europe, the Far East, Mexico and South America. The NHMA has two overseas offices, one in England and another in Hong Kong to help members in their international trade endeavors.<p>

<h4>The Central Illinois Exporters' Association</h4>

(CIEA) located in Champaign, was established in 1986 and has 47 members dedicated to the promotion of exports by companies in Central Illinois. These members range from service, agri-business, manufacturing, distribution, banking, software, law and education. CIEA sponsors six programs annually. Recent programs have focused on an introduction to exporting, the basics of exporting, export services available through the State of Illinois, developing successful export strategies, selling in Europe, and entering the Japanese market. CIEA also sponsors an annual day-long export documentation seminar, now in its ninth year.<p>

<h4>The Illinois Wheat Association </h4>

(IWA) of Champaign, is an organization dedicated to improving the production, marketing and processing of Illinois wheat. The association is made up of members from many different sectors of the wheat industry, including producers, seedsman, fertilizer and chemical dealers, merchandisers, processors, equipment manufacturers, researchers, educators and government representatives. The Association promotes exports awareness and development of Illinois products. In fact, members of the IWA board have met with several foreign trade teams to promote Illinois wheat and make them aware that Illinois is a leading state in soft red winter wheat production.<p>
</ul>

The two award winners in the new category of Community Service Recognition were:<p>
<ul>
<h4>JETRO  Chicago</h4>

the Japan External Trade Organization is a nonprofit government related organization chartered in 1958. JETRO's main objectives are to promote exports of American products to Japan. In order to accomplish these goals, JETRO has developed many programs that give American and Japanese businesses the opportunity to work together. JETRO Chicago conducts three to five major seminars in Illinois every year in order to promote export awareness from the U.S. to Japan. JETRO has worked closely with the International Business Division of the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs to promote Illinois products to Japan.<p>

<h4>The U.S. Mexico Chamber of Commerce</h4>

Mid-America Chapter in Chicago, strives to promote and foster trade, investment and good business relations between the Midwest States of the United States and the countries of North America. They also co-sponsor and cooperate with organizations for public events which enhance the commercial image of Mexico or promote U.S. Mexico and U.S. Latin America economic relations. The Mid-America Chapter, founded in 1994, has a total of  55 member organizations.<p>
</ul>

<hr>
<h3>International Business Division</h3>

DCCA's International Business Division often receives valuable tips from exporters and service organizations. Some of these developments and advice will probably affect your own company's export business. In an effort to keep our readers informed, we will begin sharing these tips and experiences in this and future issues of the Trade Leader.<p>

<hr>
<h3>Export Tips</h3>

<h4>What is an ATA Carnet?</h4>

ATA Carnet, "The Merchandise Passport" is an internationally recognized customs document that allows exporters to avoid duties and taxes on temporary imports, thereby reducing the cost of doing business internationally. ATA Carnets cover commercial samples, professional equipment, and goods for exhibitions and fairs.<p>

ATA Carnet benefits include:<p> 
<ul>
<li>NOT paying duties and taxes (VAT is a minimum of 15% in Europe).<p>

<li>NOT purchasing a temporary import bond.<p>

<li>NOT registering the goods upon departure from the United States.<p>

<li>USE ON MORE THAN ONE TRIP:  ATA Carnets are valid for up to one year and may be used for  multiple exits from and entries into
the United States and foreign countries.<p>

<li>COVERAGE OF MOST BUSINESS RELATED ITEMS:  Display booths, which are subject to duty, may  travel on Carnet.<p>

<li>PRE-DETERMINED COSTS:  Charges associated with the Carnet are paid before departure.<p>

<li>ACCEPTANCE IN OVER 50 COUNTRIES AND TERRITORIES: Thailand has recently joined the system  and China is expected to begin accepting Carnets later this year.<p>
</ul>

Companies interested in applying for an ATA Carnet should contact the United States Council for International Business at 212/354-4480.<p>

<hr>
