<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Illinois Facts: Global Access from Illinois</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>International Business Division</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>


<CENTER><H3>Global Access from Illinois</H3></CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
Illinois has long known the importance of international trade.  
Illinois created its International Business Division, housed at the 
Department of Commerce and Community Affairs, in 1965 and  was among the 
first states to open an international trade office when it opened a 
facility in Brussels, Belgium in 1968. Today the state helps businesses 
pursue international opportunities from offices in Brussels, Tokyo, Hong 
Kong, Mexico City, Warsaw and Budapest, as well as through trade leads, 
participation in trade shows, catalog shows and trade missions.  In 
addition, the International Business Division, headquartered in Chicago, 
oversees a network of International Trade Centers in five locations around 
the state to help smaller Illinois businesses achieve success in the global 
marketplace.<P>

International markets play a critical role in the Illinois economy.  
International powerhouses such as Caterpillar Inc., Deere & Company, Archer 
Daniels Midland and Motorola are headquartered in Illinois, helping to make 
Illinois the fifth largest exporting state in the nation, seventh in 
manufactured exports and second in agricultural shipments.  Exports of 
agricultural products and manufactured goods from Illinois in 1994 were 
estimated at more than $26.4 billion.  Nearly 500,000 Illinois jobs are 
linked to exports and nearly 236,000 Illinois workers are employed by 
foreign-owned firms.<P>

Illinois is home to O'Hare International Airport, the world's 
busiest, which is served by all of the major international carriers.  
Thirteen port districts are located in the state, offering companies direct 
links to the Atlantic Ocean and the Gulf of Mexico.  Foreign trade zones, 
which offer low-cost production and warehousing facilities for imported and 
export-bound products, are located at the Illinois International Port 
District in Chicago, the Tri-City Regional Port District near St. Louis, 
and in Peoria, Rockford, the Quad Cities and Lawrenceville.<P>

More than 150 export managing/trading companies and more than 100 
international freight forwarders and custom house brokers maintain offices 
in Illinois.  At least 60 foreign governments have representatives in 
Illinois and 59 nations maintain consulates in the state.<P>

Seventy international banks have established branches or 
representative offices in Chicago.  The Illinois Export Financing 
Partnership, a joint effort between the Illinois Department of Commerce and 
Community Affairs and the Illinois Development Finance Authority, also 
helps small and medium-sized exporters by packaging loans for the Working 
Capital Guarantee Program through Eximbank, the independent U.S. government 
agency that facilitates the export financing of U.S. goods and services. <P>


<CENTER><H4>Foreign Consulates in Illinois</H4></CENTER>
