<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Grain Warehouse License</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.  Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Grain Warehouse License
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Agriculture<BR>
Bureau of Warehouses<BR>
P.O. Box 19281<BR>
Springfield, IL 62794-9281<BR>
(217) 782-2895<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
114 Illinois Compiled Statutes 214.1-30 (Public Grain Warehouse & Warehouse Receipts Act)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
This license is required to operate a grain elevator, or a business engaged in the operation of a public grain warehouse, in which grain is stored for compensation.  A license allows warehousemen to store and commingle grain owned by others for compensation.  A Class I Grain Warehouse License allows a warehouseman to issue negotiable warehouse receipts to depositors (farmers).   Grain warehouse licenses must be renewed annually.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must complete and file a Grain License Application, naming the principal officers (if a corporation), the address of each warehouse, a description of all grain storage structures, the manager's name, a financial statement and other information as may be required by the Department.<P> 

Applicants must provide proof of insurance, a copy of the proposed schedule of rates to be charged and a copy of the lease agreement if applicable.  The Department can process a grain warehouse license  application in a few days.  The most common reason for denial of applications is a failure to meet the financial requirements. There is no appeal process for a denial, but another application may be submitted.<P> 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Warehousemen must provide competent personnel and equipment to weigh and grade  grain. in and out of storage.  It is the duty of every warehouseman to receive for storage any grain that may be tendered to him or her in the ordinary course of business so far as the capacity of the warehouse permits and the grain is of the kind customarily stored therein, and is in suitable condition for storage.<P> 

The warehouseman shall keep stocks of grain in storage in balance by quantity and quality with the grain represented by outstanding storage obligations.  Warehouseman must maintain licensed grain storage facilities in a manner suitable to preserve the quality and quantity of grain stored.  Each warehouseman must insure grain for its full market value against loss or damage. Warehousemen must allow inspectors access to all facilities and records at least once a year.<P>
</DD></DL>
	
<HR>
<H3>VII:  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
The fee for a license is $100.<P>
The fee to amend licensed storage capacity is $50.<P>
The cost to renew annual financial statements is $25.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
