<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Illinois Commercial Feed Act</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>


<H3>I.   Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Commercial Feed Act<P>
<DL><DD>
1.)  License to Manufacture Commercial Feed<P>
2.)  Registration of Commercial Feed<P>
</DD></DL>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Agriculture<BR>
P.O. Box 19281<BR>
Springfield, IL 62794-9281<BR>
Bureau of Agricultural Products Inspection<BR>
(217) 785-8356<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III. Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
505 Illinois Compiled Statutes 30/1 et seq. (Illinois Commercial Feed Act)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV. Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Manufacturers of commercial animal feeds and customer-formula feeds must be licensed by the Department.  Commercial animal feed (except customer-formula feeds) must be registered with the Department.  A license and registration authorizes an animal feed manufacturer to grind, mix, blend or further process a commercial feed for distribution.  A violation of these requirements is a business offense.  License are valid for one calendar year or any portion of a calendar year.  Registrations for animal feed products are permanent unless amended or canceled by registrant.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
To obtain a license, applicants must complete and file with the Department Form# IL406-1480 (12-91), an "Application for Feed Distribution/Manufacturing Facility License".  To register a commercial animal feed, applicants must complete and file with the Department an "Application for Registration of Commercial Feed" form and a "Report of Inspection Fees for Pet Food and Specialty Pet Food Products in Small Containers of 10# or Less" form.  (Customer-formula feeds are exempt from registration.)<P>   

Applications for Registration must be accompanied by a package label and other information required describing the product.  The average processing time for both the license and registration applications is  three weeks.  A registration of a product may be denied if the product does not meet the labeling requirements.  If denied, the process is subject to the Administrative Review Law.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI. Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Records must be kept on tonnage of commercial feed distributed.   Inspectors must have access to all records during business hours.<P>

Licensed facilities must be inspected every two years, and available for inspection during business hours. Vehicles used to transport or hold feeds must be available for inspection.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII. Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Licenses: $25.<P>

(There is no fee for Registration of a product)<P>

Inspection fee: 16 cents per ton on all products not packaged in 10 pound units or less. Inspection fee on  small-packaged pet foods (under 10 pounds) is $50 per year on each product. <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
