<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: License for a Bonded Warehouse</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.  Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
License for a Bonded Warehouse
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Agriculture<BR>
Bureau of Warehouses<BR>
P.O. Box 19281<BR>
Springfield, IL 62794-9281<BR>
(217) 782-2895<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
240 Illinois Compiled Statutes 10/1 et seq  (Personal Property Warehouse Act)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
This license is required before anyone may store goods for compensation, such as a moving van company, boat storage facility, commercial distribution center. The license permits a business to store for a fee, advertise, and solicit for business as a bonded warehouse.  Conducting business without a license is a Class B misdemeanor for the first violation and  a Class A misdemeanor thereafter.  The license is for the term of one year.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must complete and file form #IL406-0060, fees and insurance.  Upon receipt of an application, fees, and insurance forms by the Department, an inspector conducts a pre-licensing exam. Applications are processed in approximately one week. Common reasons for denial is applicant's failure to obtain insurance; a building is not secure or inadequate fire protection. Denied applications are subject to the Administrative Hearing Review. 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Licensed warehousemen must use reasonable care and diligence to protect stored property from loss or damage by fire, theft, burglary or other similar causes; keep and maintain suitable premises for such storage purposes; keep records showing all property in storage, all warehouse receipts issued, or canceled, and any other information necessary to the proper conduct of the business in accordance with the Act. Records must be kept for one year after closing any storage transaction.<P> 

Stored liquor must have a certificate of registration from the Department of Revenue.  The warehouse must be accessible for inspection at any reasonable time.  The warehouseman must file a surety bond with the Department or a liability insurance policy.  Numbered warehouse receipts must be printed on a form prescribed by the Department.<P>

Negotiable warehouse receipts forms must be kept under lock and key at the warehouse office.  A register must be kept of each negotiable warehouse receipt issued.  The operator must keep a sign posted in a conspicuous place over the main entrance to each warehouse showing the name of the business and the license number issued by the Department.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
An annual initial warehouse license is $250, plus $100 for each additional warehouse.  An annual warehouse license renewal fee is $150, plus $100 for each additional warehouse.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
