<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: License for Livestock Auction Markets.</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.  Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
License for Livestock Auction Markets.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Agriculture<BR>
Bureau of Animal Health<BR>
P.O. Box 19281<BR>
Springfield, IL 62794-9281<BR>
(217) 782-4944<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
121 1/2 Illinois Compiled Statutes 208, 640/1-12.(Livestock Auction Market Law)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A license is required to operate a livestock auction market (defined as a market where livestock is assembled for sale or exchange, or where livestock is sold or exchanged at auction, more frequently than 3 times during the preceding 12 months).  This license authorizes a business to hold, operate, conduct, or carry-on a livestock  auction market in Illinois.  Conducting a livestock auction market without a license is a petty offense, and each day of unlicensed operation constitutes a separate offense.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must complete and file an "Application for License to Conduct a Livestock Auction Market" (naming the operator, the location of the premises, the type of livestock to be handled, sold, or exchanged, a description of the facilities, and the name of the accredited veterinarian who will supervise the market.), and "Application for Permit for Official Veterinarian of Livestock Auction Market", Form #M-908.<P> 
 
The licensing process takes about 2 weeks, during which time the Market's scales and the facilities (the yards and the housing for the veterinarian) must be inspected.  An application may be denied if  applicant is not qualified or the premises do not pass inspection.  Denied applications may be appealed under the terms of the Administrative Review Law.<P>	
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicant must file a surety bond, a trust fund agreement, or a letter of credit for a minimum of $10,000 with the Department.  Applicant must obtain an accredited veterinarian to supervise the market (Form M-908).  The Licensee must maintain a separate bank account identified in such a way as to disclose  that the depository is acting as a fiduciary and that the funds in the account are trust funds.<P>

The license must be conspicuously displayed in the sale ring or some other prominent place. Licensee must observe state sanitation laws to prevent Bovine or Swine Brucellosis and Bovine Tuberculosis, and maintain sanitary yarding, housing, holding, and feeding areas.  Scales must be inspected by a state inspector 2 times per year.  A schedule of the fees or commission rates charged for livestock sold or handled must be posted.<P> 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII. Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
The License fee is $200.00.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
