<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: License for selling, breeding, boarding, and/or training pets, cats and dogs.</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I. Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
License for selling, breeding, boarding, and/or training pets, cats and dogs.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II. Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Agriculture<BR> 
Bureau of Animal Welfare<BR>
P.O. Box 19281<BR>
Springfield, IL 62794-9281<BR>
(217) 782-6657<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III. Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
225 Illinois Compiled Statutes 605/1-22. (Animal Welfare Act)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV. Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
This license is required for a pet shop, dog dealer, canine and/or feline breeder, kennel, cattery, pound or shelter, and allows the business to sell, board, train or breed animals for retail. (No license is required if the facility involves less than 6 female cats or dogs capable of production.)  Only one license is required for any combination of these businesses at one location.  Any person conducting these businesses without a license is guilty of a petty offense.  Licenses are valid for one year (from July 1 of the year issued, and expire the following June 30).
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V. Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must complete and file with the Department Form # AW-1,  together with appropriate fee. Before a license will be issued, the Department will inspect the  proposed facility. If the facility doesn't pass inspection, the applicant may enter into a Work Progress Agreement with the Department. (A Work Progress Agreement describes the specific things that must be done to satisfy Department inspection requirements.) Inspections are usually accomplished within three weeks.  Once the Department approves a facility the applicant may open for business immediately.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI. Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
License holders must maintain, and keep available for the Department's inspection, records regarding the origin and sale of all dogs, maintain facilities according to local and Department sanitary and health standards, meet all local zoning ordinances and comply with the Assumed Name Act.  The license must be prominently displayed at each place of business covered by the license.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
$25 annually.  Payment can be made by check or money order payable to the Illinois Department of Agriculture.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
