<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: License for the collection and disposal of dead animals.</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.  Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
License for the collection and disposal of dead animals.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II. Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Agriculture<BR>
Bureau of Animal Welfare<BR>
P.O. Box 19281<BR>
Springfield, IL 62794-9281<BR>
(217) 782-6657<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III. Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
225 Illinois Compiled Statutes 610/1.1-19a.  (Illinois Dead Animal Disposal Act)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV. Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A license is required to operate a business that provides animal collection services to rendering plants.  A license authorizes the disposal of bodies or parts of bodies of dead animals, poultry or fish, or used cooking grease and oil.  Licensed businesses may salvage hides, wool, skins or feathers and produce, animal, poultry, or fish protein, blood meal, bone meal, grease or tallow.  Conducting these business services without the appropriate license is a Class C misdemeanor.  Licenses are valid for one year.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V. Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must complete and file with the Department Form # M-93,  containing information about the proposed business including its location, the  method intended to be used for disposal of rendering material and other required information.  The Department will inspect the proposed building and equipment before issuing a license.<P> 

If the facility doesn't pass inspection, the applicant may enter into a Work Progress Agreement with the Department.  (A Work Progress Agreement describes the specific things that must be done to satisfy Department inspection requirements.)   The licensing process usually takes about 30 days. <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI. Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
An adequate water supply must be available to the proposed facility.  Applicant must get a permit for trucks used to convey inedible animal products to the facility (available by completing and filing Form # T-3 with the Department's Bureau of Animal Welfare) and meet all local zoning ordinances.<P>

Rendering material must be processed or disposed of within 48 hours after delivery to the plant. Odors must be controlled and steam disposed of in compliance with EPA requirements. Department Inspectors must have access to the facility during usual working hours.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII. Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Type A (Dead Animals Only) $150.<P>
Type B (Parts of Bodies of Animals, Bone, Fat, Scrap, Used Cooking Grease or Oils)  $150.<P>
Type C (Poultry or Parts of Poultry)  $150.<P>
Type D (Fish or Parts of Fish) $150.<P>
Type E (Blender) $150.<P>
Type F (Collection Center) $25.<P>
Type G (Animal Collection Service)  $25. <P>
Annual Truck Permit $10.<P> 
(Each additional rendering license (Type A - E) requires a $50 fee.)<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
