<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: License to Sell and/or Break Eggs</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.   Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
License to Sell and/or Break Eggs
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Agriculture<BR>
Bureau of Weights & Measures<BR>
State Fairgrounds, P.O.Box 19281<BR>
Springfield, IL 62794-9281<BR>
(217) 785-8252<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III. Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
410 Illinois Compiled Statutes 615 / Sect. 13 Illinois Egg and Egg Products Act
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Title 8  Illinois Administrative Code, Part 65.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A License is required to sell, trade or barter eggs or process liquid frozen or dried eggs.<P>

A license authorizes the sale of eggs to a store, restaurant, school,
hospital, nursing home or bakery, or between dealers.  Each location where
eggs are sold must be licensed.<P>

Conducting these business operations without a License is a Class A
Misdemeanor and subject to fines from $100 to $500 or imprisonment for up
to six months.<P>

A License is valid for one year, from July 1 to June 30 the following
year.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.   Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must file an "Application for an Egg License" Form# IL 406-0039, together with a current financial statement. There are two categories of Licenses:  (1) Limited License for producers with less than 3,000 birds who grade and sell their own eggs, and  (2) Full License, for all of the following: a.) producer-dealers who sell other than his/her own production; b.) grading station; c.) jobber-brokers; d.) distributor.  The average processing time for a license is three weeks.<P>

     Licenses will not be issued if an application lacks required
information. In those cases, applicants may correct deficiencies and
resubmit their applications for further consideration.  Decisions of the
Department are subject to Illinois Administrative Procedures.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
     Invoices must show seller and receiver's name and address, the egg
grade, size, quantity, and inspection fee if applicable.<P>

     Records must be maintained for two years and available for Department
inspection during business hours.  <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII. Fees: </H3>
<DL><DD>
Licenses:<P>
<DL><DD>
1. <EM>Full: </EM>            $30.00<P>
2. <EM>Limited:</EM>          $5.00<P>
3. <EM>Inspection Fee:</EM>   $.05 cents / 30 dozen case sold in Illinois.<BR>
                    The first seller pays the fee.
                    The out-of-state seller pays the fee.<P>

4. <EM>Egg Breaking:</EM>     $200.00<P>
</DD></DL>
</DD></DL>


<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
