<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Nurseryman's & Nursery Dealers Certification</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.  Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Nurseryman's & Nursery Dealers Certification
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Agriculture<BR>
Bureau of Environmental Programs<BR>
P.O. Box 19281<BR>
Springfield, IL 62794-9281<BR>
(217) 785-2427<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
505 Illinois Compiled Statutes 90   (Insect Pest and Plant Disease Act.)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A Nurserymen's Certificate is required to own, lease, manage or operate a nursery, grow or propagate nursery stock.  A Nursery Dealer Certificate is required to operate orchards, greenhouses, a landscaping business, Christmas tree farms, or any business that ships or sells plants (like Lowes, Walmart, etc.).  Operating these businesses without a Certificate is a Class B misdemeanor for the first violation and a Class A misdemeanor for subsequent violations, and subject to fines of up to $10,000.  A Nurseryman's Certificate and Nursery Dealer Registration are valid for 1 year.  
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants for a Nurserymen's Certificate must complete and file an "Application for Nurseryman's Certificate".  The Department will inspect the nursery facility and stock. If the inspection shows no infestation of insect pests or plant diseases, the Department will issue the Certificate. If pests or disease are found, the Certification is withheld until those conditions have been corrected.<P>  

Each location must be certified by the Department.<P>

Applicants for a Nursery Dealer Certificate  must complete and file an "Application for Nursery Dealer Registration".  Only nursery stock that has been inspected and certified can be sold or delivered.  Both Certification processes usually take about 10 days after inspections have been completed.  Denied applications may be appealed under the terms of the Administrative Review Law.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Businesses must allow Department inspectors to have access to any place that might become infested with insect pests or disease.<P>

The business must keep records of plant purchases, acquisitions, sales or distributions for 1 year and give notice to the Department of nursery stock received from foreign countries.  Records must be available to Department inspectors on request.  The certificate of inspection must be prominently displayed at the business's main office.  All nursery stock must be stored in such a way as to maintain plant health.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
<STRONG><EM>For nursery inspection:</EM></STRONG><P>

1 acre or less = $15;<BR>
One to 5 acres = $20;<BR>
Five to 10 acres =$25;<BR>
Ten to 50 acres =$35;<BR>
Fifty to 100 acres =$50;<BR>
One hundred acres to 250 acres =$100;<BR>
Two hundred fifty acres to 500 acres =$125;<BR>
More than 500 acres =35 cents per acre.<P>

The fee for the Nursery Dealer Certificate is $15 for the main location and $15 for each additional location.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
