<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Franchise Certificate of Registration </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I. Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Franchise Certificate of Registration 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II. Agency: </H3>
<DL><DD>
Attorney General<BR>
Franchise Bureau<BR>
500 South 2nd St.<BR>
Springfield, IL 62706<BR>
(217) 782-4465,  TDD# (217) 785-2771<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
815 Illinois Compiled Statutes 705 (Franchises)
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulations:</H3>
<DL><DD>
14 Illinois Administrative Code  A, II, 200  (Franchise Disclosure Act)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV. Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Before selling or offering to sell a franchise in Illinois, an individual or business must register with the Attorney General and provide full financial disclosure  as required by the Act . (Exceptions to these requirements are banks and insurance companies, or businesses exempted from the requirement by an Administrator appointed by the Attorney General.)  Registration of a franchisor and the disclosure statement shall continue to be effective until the Administrator suspends, terminates, or denies registration or sale of a franchise.  A person selling a franchise in Illinois without registration, or who files a false or misleading disclosure statement, is guilty of a class 2 felony and may be fined up to $50,000 per violation.  The purpose of this requirement is to provide protections to prospective Illinois investor-residents  requiring full and complete financial information about franchises marketed in Illinois.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V. Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Franchisors must register by completing and filing an application and financial disclosure statement.  The Administrator may require additional information of the applicant to protect the public interest.   The registration becomes effective 20 business day after filing, unless the applicant is otherwise notified.  If the Administrator determines that additional information or further modifications are required, he or she may suspend a franchisor's right to sell until specified deficiencies are cured.  An Administrator may require an escrow account be established and impound fees or other funds until all obligations have been fulfilled, or a surety bond is furnished.  Registration may be denied, or registration suspended or terminated by an order of the Administrator, if an application/registration form is incomplete or if an annual report disclosure statement is deficient. In such a case the Administrator gives written notice to the  applicant or registered party, who may then request a hearing to modify or vacate the Administrator's order.
</DD></DL>  

<HR>
<H3>VI. Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Franchisors must file an annual report and current disclosure statement.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII. Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
The initial registration of a franchise is $500.  An amended disclosure statement is $25;  an amendment constituting a material change is $100.  An Attorney General's opinion interpreting the Act is $50. An annual report filing fee is $100.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
