<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Qualified Solid Waste Energy Facility </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.	Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Qualified Solid Waste Energy Facility 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.	Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Commerce Commission<BR>
527 East Capitol, P.O. Box 19280<BR>
Springfield, IL  62794-9280<BR>
Office of Policy and Planning<BR>
(217) 524-5041<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.	Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
220 Illinois Compiled Statutes 5/8-403.1 (Public Utilities Act)<P>
415 Illinois Compiled Statutes 10/3.1 (Local Solid Waste Disposal Act)<P>
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
83 Illinois Administrative Code Parts 200 (Rules of Practice) and 445 (Purchase and Sale of Electric Energy From Qualified Solid Waste Energy Facilities)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.	Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
In order to be designated as a Qualified Solid Waste Energy Facility (QSWEF), electric generating facilities fueled by either methane gas from a landfill or from the incineration of solid waste must meet specific criteria.  Illinois electric public utilities are required to enter 10-year (landfill gas) or 20-year (solid waste) contracts to purchase the electricity generated by the QSWEFs located in their respective service territories at rates that are approximately equal to the average rates that units of local government (e.g., cities or counties) pay the utility for electric service. The public utilities who purchase the electricity are entitled to tax credits equal to the difference between the amount paid for electricity and the amount that they would have otherwise been required to pay such facilities for electricity under the federal law (federal Public Utilities Regulatory Policies Act of 1978). At the end of its contract, a QSWEF is required to begin repaying the State for the tax credits taken by the utility for purchasing its power.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
The owners or operators of an electric generating facility must file a petition with the Illinois Commerce Commission seeking a determination that the facility meets the criteria for QSWEF status. The Commission will hold a public hearing to determine whether the facility qualifies.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
The owners or operators of an electric generating facility must be able to demonstrate compliance with the requirements for QSWEF status that are set forth in the Public Utilities Act and Local Solid Waste Disposal Act, and if QSWEF status is granted, file reports with the Illinois Commerce Commission demonstrating their continuing compliance with such requirements.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.	Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
There are no filing fees.
</DD></DL>


<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
