<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Water or Sewer Service: Certificate of Public Convenience and Necessity for Operation of a Public Utility</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.	Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Water or Sewer Service: Certificate of Public Convenience and Necessity for Operation of a Public Utility
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.	Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Commerce Commission<BR>
527 East Capitol, P.O. Box 19280<BR>
Springfield, IL 62794-9280<BR>
Office of Policies & Planning/Public Utilities Division<BR>
(217) 524-0671<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.	Statute: </H3>
<DL><DD>
220 Illinois Compiled Statutes 5/8-406. (Public Utilities Act)
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
83 Illinois Administrative Code Part 200  (Rules of Practice) 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.	Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A Certificate of Public Convenience and Necessity ("Certificate") allows a public utility to provide water or sewer service and/or to construct new plants, equipment, and facilities for providing such service. A Certificate remains effective until the service is deemed no longer necessary to the public convenience.<P>

* A "Public Utility" is an investor owned business that sells or delivers electricity, gas, water, or sewer services for public use. <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants for a Certificate should file a petition with the Commission following the process explained in its "Rules of Practice".  The Commission can issue a certificate if it finds, after a public hearing, that the utility's purpose for the certificate promotes the public convenience and necessity.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants for a Certificate have the legal burden of proving to the Commission that issuance of a Certificate will promote the public convenience and necessity.<P>

A Public Utility must pay an annual regulatory tax at 0.1% on gross revenues.<P>

Public Utilities must file an annual report.  <P>

Public Utilities must file tariffs, or changes in its tariffs, with the Commission before providing service.	<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.	Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
There are no fees for a certificate. (The Public Utilities Act requires a fee for the issuance of stocks, bonds, notes and other instruments of indebtedness.) 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
