<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Illinois Chemical Safety Act (ICSA)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I. Business Requirement Profile:</H3>

<DL><DD>Illinois Chemical Safety Act (ICSA)</DD></DL>
<HR>
<H3>II. Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>               Illinois Emergency Management Agency   (IEMA)<BR>
               Operations Division<BR>
               Hazardous Materials Compliance & Enforcement Section<BR>
               110 E. Adams<BR>
               Springfield, IL 62701<BR>
               (217) 782-4694</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III. Statute Citation:</H3>

<DL><DD>430 Illinois Compiled Statutes 45</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV. Requirement Description:</H3>

<DL><DD>The purpose of the ICSA is to establish an
orderly system to assure that owners and/or operators of business
facilities are adequately prepared to respond to a release of chemical
substances into the environment and to improve the ability of State and
local authorities to respond to such releases.  Businesses subject to ICSA
regulations are those assigned or included within the Standard Industrial
Classifications (SIC) named in the Act 430 ILCS 45/3.  The requirements of
Act also apply to businesses that are subject to the provisions of Section
302 of the federal Emergency Planning and Community Right-to-Know Act
(EPCRA) of 1986 and  use, store and/or manufacture a chemical substance in
a quantity that poses a threat to the environment or public health.  The
ICSA requires business owners/operators to prepare a written Chemical
Contingency Safety Plan (unless exempted by the statute), to maintain a
copy of it on the business site, and provide copies to the local emergency
response agencies.  These businesses must certify in writing to IEMA that a
Chemical Contingency Safety Plan has been developed and provided to the
local planning and response agencies and the dates that the plans were
delivered to local officials.</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V. Approval Process:</H3>

<DL><DD>None.  However, the IEMA may issue an exemption from
these requirements for chemical substances used or stored in innocuous
amounts that are not likely to result in a release that threatens the
environment or the public health.  Exemptions are issued on the basis of an
on site inspection of a facility.</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI. Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>

<DL><DD>Requirements of the
ICSA apply to businesses with 5 or more full-time employees, or 20 or more
part-time employees, that is assigned any of the Standard Industrial
Classifications (SIC) codes listed in the Act.</DD>
</DL>
<HR>
<H3>VII. Fees:</H3>

<DL><DD>None.</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
