<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Non-hazardous Waste Landfill Permit   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.	Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Non-hazardous Waste Landfill Permit   
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II. 	Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Environmental Protection Agency<BR>
Bureau of Land / Permits Section<BR>
1340 North Ninth St.<BR>
Springfield, IL 62703<BR>
(217) 524-3300<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III. Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
415 Illinois Compiled Statutes 5/1 et seq.   (Illinois Environmental Protection Act)
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
35 Illinois Administrative Code 811-814 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.	Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
The purpose of the Permit is to protect groundwater, surface water, air and the land from activities that cause pollution. <P>

A Permit is required before an existing landfill operator may accept non-hazardous waste for disposal or before an landfill operator may modify the development or operation of an existing landfill. A Permit is required before a new landfill may be developed. Once developed, a second Permit is required before a new landfill may begin operations. <P>

Operating a facility without a Permit or operating a facility in non-compliance with Agency requirements, may result in penalties including enforced compliance, penalties and/or a jail term.  Penalties range in severity according to the level and duration of the infringement.<P>

Non-hazardous waste landfill Permits are valid for a maximum 5 years and may be renewed.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V. 	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants to own/operate a non-hazardous landfills must complete and file with the Agency application forms LPC-PA1, LPC-PA2 and LPC-PA16 to IEPA.<P>

New or expanding facilities must file form #LPC-PA8, demonstrating local siting approval.<P>

Applicants to develop a new or existing landfill must complete and file form #LPC-PA2.  <P>

Applications must be signed and bear the seal of an Illinois licensed Professional Engineer.<P>

Applications to develop a new facility or expand an existing one are usually processed in 180 days.Renewal and Modification applications for existing landfill facilities are usually processed in 90 days. Permit holders must adhere to the restrictions of the Permit, such as not land-filling at an unpermitted area, protecting the environment and conforming to the Environmental Protection Act's requirements. The most common reason for denial is due to technical deficiencies in the application. Denied applications may be appealed to the Pollution Control Board.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI. 	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
<EM>Pre-Requisites:</EM>  Siting approval from the local governing body must accompany an application to develop a new or expand an existing landfill.<P>

<EM>Post-Requisite:</EM>  Permit holders must file  a quarterly report including monitoring information (leachate, groundwater, and gas monitoring), and an annual report on the amount, type and original location of waste received at the facility, monitoring information and facility modification information. Permit holders must provide at least 30 years of post-closure care and financial assistance.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII. Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
None.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
