<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Permit for construction & operation of sanitary sewer connections, sanitary sewer extensions, sewage treatment plant, pretreatment facilities, land application of sludge/wastewater and agrichemical facility permits.</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.   Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Permit for construction & operation of sanitary sewer connections, sanitary sewer extensions, sewage treatment plant, pretreatment facilities, land application of sludge/wastewater and agrichemical facility permits.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Environmental Protection Agency<BR>
Bureau of Water / Division of Water Pollution Control<BR>
2200 Churchill Road<BR>
Springfield, IL 62794-9276<BR>
(217) 782-0610<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III. Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
415 Illinois Compiled Statutes 5/Section 12 & 39  (Environmental Protection Act)
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Title 35, Illinois Administrative Code, Section 309.201-282.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV. Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A Permit is required to operate or construct a water treatment works, pretreatment water works, sewers and wastewater sources.  The purpose of the Permit requirement is to allow the Agency to review projects to assure their conformance with statutory and rule requirements and agency criteria, and to protect waters of the State from contaminants that would jeopardize the public health.  Violations of this requirement may result in fines of $5,000 plus $10,000 for each day a violation continues.<P>

Permits remain valid until construction is complete.  (Permits for sewers or waste water sources require construction be competed within 2 years.  Permits for treatment works or pretreatment works require construction be completed within 3 years.)  Operating permits remain valid for up to 5 years.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must file an "Application for Permit or Construction Approval" together with a description of the project, construction plans and specifications, a design of the project prepared by an Illinois Registered Professional Engineer and be signed by the appropriate principal executive officers, ranking elected officials or authorized employee.<P>

The Agency has 90 days to respond to applications for permit unless a fee is required.  When a fee is required, the Agency has 45 days.<P>

An application will be denied if it is not complete or does not conform with Agency design criteria or the standards for issuance.  The application may be corrected and resubmitted.  Denied applications may be appealed to the Illinois Pollution Control Board.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI. Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
The Agency may impose conditions on a Permit which may require monitoring or reporting to the Agency.
</DD></DL>

<H3>VII. Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
<STRONG><EM>Permits:</EM></STRONG> $50 for a sewer constructed with a design population of 1.  $200 for a population of 2 to 20;  $400 for a population of 21 to 100;  $600 for a population from 101 to 500;  $1,200 for a population over 500. <P>

<STRONG><EM>Exception:</EM></STRONG>   These fees do not apply to sewers paid for entirely by a unit of state or local government or a school district.)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
