<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Permit for Coal Mining & Coal Mining Related Activities, including Coal Refuse Disposal</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>


<H3>I.   Business Requirement Profile:</H3>

<DL><DD>Permit for Coal Mining & Coal Mining Related Activities, including Coal Refuse Disposal</DD>
</DL>
<HR>                    
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
             <DL> <DD> Illinois Environmental Protection Agency<BR>
               Bureau of Water / Mine Pollution Control Program<BR>
               2309 West Main St.<BR>
               Marion, IL 62959<BR>
               (618) 993-7200<BR></DD></DL>

<HR>          
<H3>III. Statute & Regulation "Citing": </H3>

<DL><DD>415 ILCS 5/Section 12 & 13 of
Environmental Protection Act.  Title 35, Illinois Admin. Code, Sub. D:
Mine Related Water Pollution</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV. Requirement Description:</H3>

<DL><DD><P>The purpose of the permit program is to
provide assurance that planning is provided for proper environmental
safeguards for the location, preparation, operation and abandonment of
mining, mining related activities and mine refuse disposal operations in
order to prevent pollution of waters within the state.  Mining and mining
related activities include the surface or underground extraction or
processing of natural deposits of coal by the use of any mechanical
operation or process.  The term mining also includes the recovery or
processing of coa from a mine refuse area.

<P>Related activities refers to all activities at a facility which are
directly in furtherance of mining, including activities before, during and
after mining.  Such related activities include but are not limited to coal
refuse disposal and coal combustion waste (CCW) disposal.  The term mining
related activities does not include land acquisition, exploratory drilling,
surveying and similar activities.  Also included in the Mine Pollution
Control Program permit process is coal transfer facilities and coal storage
yards (exluding consumer stockpiles) which is defined as any areas where
coal is transferred from one mode of transportation to another or where
coal is dumped, piled, stored or blended.

<P>Coal docks, blending yards, conveyor belts and pipelines are also included
herein.  Conducting Mining or Mine related activities without a permit is a
civiil penalty punishable by a fee of not more than $10,000/day that
violations are occuring.  The permit generally remains effective for a
period of 5 years at which time a renewal is required.  If a renewal
application is submitted at least 180 days prior to permit expiration, a
standard condition will allow the permit to remain effective until such
time as the renewal is addressed.</DD></DL>
<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>

<DL><DD><P>In order to obtain a permit (Subtitle D or NPDES),
an application must be completed and submitted directly to the IEPA.  In
instances of a new facility construction or significant revisions to
existing facilities, a permit is not only required by the IEPA but also
from the Illinois Department of Mines & Minerals (IDMM).  If this is the
case, the application to IDMM may be used as a joint application to the
IEPA, if so indicated.  All applications to the agency, whether a direct
submittal or submitted as a joint application to IDMM/IEPA, shall be
complete and include all items and requirements identified in Title 35,
Illinois Admin. Code, 405.104.

<P>All applications are reviewed by the IEPA for completeness, accuracy and
compliance with mine related environmental regulations.  Reasons for denial
of a permit from the IEPA -Mine Pollution Control Program would include any
proposed activity that threatens or allows the discharge of contaminants
into waters of the state.  Any permit denial can be appealed to the
Illinois Pollution Control Board.  The average processing time for a new
locations is generally quite timely and by comparison, shorter than for
renewals.</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI. Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>

<DL><DD><P>All applications
submitted shall be signed by a principal executive officer of at least the
level of vice-president or his duly authorized representative, if such
representative is responsible for overall operation of the facility.

<P>All plans, reports, specifications and applications submitted shall be
certified by a registered professional engineer when required by the
Illinois Professional Engineering Act.  Monitoring and reporting of surface
discharges to indicate compliance with applicable effluent standards
Submission of groundwater monitoring reports as required.  All facilities
must provide access for agency inspections.</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII. Fees:</H3>

<DL><DD>There are no fees for permits issued to coal mines and/or
coal mine related facilities by the IEPA - Mine Pollution Control Program.</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
