<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Permit for the management of hazardous waste.  (RCRA - Resource Conservation & Recovery Act/Part B Permit)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.	Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Permit for the management of hazardous waste.  (RCRA - Resource Conservation & Recovery Act/Part B Permit)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.	Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Environmental Protection Agency<BR>
Bureau of Land / Disposal Alternatives Unit or RCRA Unit<BR>
1340 N. Ninth St.<BR>
Springfield, IL 62703<BR>
(217) 524-3300<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.	Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
415 Illinois Compiled Statutes 5/39 (d).   42 USCode 6925.
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Title 35 Illinois Administrative Code Part 703.123
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.	Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A "Part B" (RCRA) Resource Conservation & Recovery Permit authorizes a person to conduct hazardous waste-storage, hazardous waste-treatment or hazardous waste-disposal operations. Storage and some treatment of on-site generated wastes may be exempt.<P>

Unlawful activities involving hazardous wastes may be prosecuted as a Class A misdemeanor or Class 1 - 4 felony.<P>

A "Part B" Permit may be issued for a period not to exceed 10 years.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must provide the information specified in the regulation. This may be accomplished by submitting the information identified in the decision guide (available from the IEPA).<P>

Applications for a new facility usually take about two years to issue.  The agency must conduct a review of the application for a new facility within thirty days after receiving the application to ensure all items have been addressed.  Once a permit application is complete, a technical review begins.<P>

If a permit is denied, it is usually denied because of technical deficiencies.<P>

If the agency denies an application or grants a permit with conditions, applicant may, within 35 days, appeal the decision and petition for a hearing before the Pollution Control Board.  The appeal may be resolved through negotiations with the agency before the Board's hearing and the negotiations may result in a revised permit.  If the hearing does take place, the burden of proof is on the petitioner.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A facility that proposes to manage waste received from an outside source must provide proof of local siting approval on Form # LPC-PA8 together with it's application. <P>

Technical data, including design drawings, specifications and engineering studies, must be certified by a professional engineer licensed to practice in Illinois.<P>

Applications must include a prior conduct certification evaluation, Form LPC 372.<P>

A facility that receives hazardous waste from outside sources, or a generator of more than 2,200 lbs. of hazardous waste per month, must submit an annual hazardous waste report to the agency by March 1, of each year. Permits commonly include conditions that require operators to 1) conduct periodic site inspections, 2) conduct groundwater monitoring, 3) provide financial assurance for closure/post-closure liability, 4) conduct soil testing for site assessment or closure, and 5) provide notification to the Agency when the facility has a fire, spill or explosion.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.	Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
None.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
