<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Permits for the management of non-hazardous solid waste (i.e., storage, treatment or disposal) of off-site generated wastes</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.	Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Permits for the management of non-hazardous solid waste (i.e., storage, treatment or disposal) of off-site generated wastes
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.	Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Environmental Protection Agency<BR>
Bureau of Land/Permits<BR>
Disposal Alternatives Unit re:  storage/treatment<BR>
Solid Waste Unit re:  garbage transfer stations/landfills<BR>
1340 N. Ninth St.<BR>
Springfield, IL 62703<BR>
(217) 524-3300<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.	Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
415 Illinois Compiled Statutes 5/1   (Illinois Environmental Protection Act.)
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Title 35, Illinois Administration Code, Parts 807.201-203, & 807.210.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.	Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A Development Permit authorizes the construction or installation of a "unit" (meaning any device, mechanism, equipment or area used for storage, treatment or disposal of waste, prior to September 18,1990).   An Operating Permit authorizes the use of a waste treatment, waste storage or waste disposal operation.  An Experimental Permit authorizes use of a process or technique that does not satisfy the requirements set forth in this Section when the applicant submits proof that the process or technique has a reasonable chance of success and the environmental hazards are minimal.<P>

A Supplemental Permit is the mechanism by which these permits are modified to reflect changes in the facility or regulations under which the facility operates.<P>

The permits apply to facilities that receive wastes from off-site.  Storage, treatment and disposal, within the site where such wastes are generated, are conditionally exempt from Permit requirements. However, the agency may require a Permit for these activities through enforcement proceedings if conditions warrant it.<P>

Conducting these activities without a permit may result in civil suits by the State's Attorney, the Attorney General's Office or any third party alleging violations of the Act.<P>

Development or Operating Permits don't expire. Experimental permits may be valid for up to 2 years. Landfill and composting permits are valid for up to 5 years.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants for a Development Permit must file Forms LPC-PA1, LPC-PA3, LPC-PA8 and LPC-PA16. <P>

(For oil storage facilities, substitute Form LPC-PA13 instead of LPC-PA3.) 
(For "potentially infectious medical waste", substitute Form# LPC-PA17 in place of  LPC-PA3.) <P>

(For landfills, substitute LPC-PA2 instead of LPC-PA3.) (For composting, substitute LPC-PA6 instead of LPC-PA3.) <P>

For landscape waste composting, substitute LPC-PA12 instead of LPC-PA3.) 
Guidance is available for "land treatment of petroleum contaminated soils" and should be considered before submitting an application for that activity.  <P>

Applications for an Operating Permit must include Forms LPC-PA1, LPC-PA4 & LPC-PA16. Applications for an Experimental Permit require the same forms as a Development or Operating Permit, together with an explanation of the proposed experimental process and proof or reasons why the process should be allowed and why the process poses a minimal environmental threat..<P>

Applicants for Supplemental Permits must submit the forms appropriate for the type (i.e. development or operating or experimental) of permit being modified. <P>

The Agency has: 1) 90 days to reach a decision on solid waste permits (nonhazardous), but usually reaches a decision in 60 days; 2) 45 days for operating permits (where construction has been completed), but the Agency usually reaches a decision within 30 days. The review period for an existing landfill (which was not required to go through siting), and new landfills, will be 180 days.Permits for the management of non-hazardous solid waste (i.e., storage, treatment or disposal) of off-site generated wastes.<P>

The most common reasons Permit applications are denied is due to technical deficiencies such as not providing secondary containment around tanks and/or containers. <P>

If an application is denied, the applicant may appeal the decision to the Pollution Control. In the hearing the burden of proof is on the applicant. The denial may be resolved through negotiations with the agency before the Board holds the hearing. The negotiations may result in a revised permit.  <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Facilities managing waste received from an outside source must receive local siting approval before a Permit application may be filed with the Agency.<P>

Technical data, such as design drawings, specifications and engineering studies which accompany applications must be certified and sealed by a  professional engineer licensed to practice in Illinois.<P>

Facilities accepting nonhazardous special waste, must file an annual report with the Agency by February 1 of each year, specifying the quantities and disposition of the waste accepted during the previous year. <P>

Permits will usually specify inspection requirements, groundwater monitoring (in some instances), financial assurance for closure (for landfills) and soil testing (for remediation  of contaminated soils). <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII. Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
None.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
