<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Underground Injection of Fluid Permit</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I. 	Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Underground Injection of Fluid Permit
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II. 	Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Environmental Protection Agency<BR>
Bureau of Land / Permits Section<BR>
1340 N. Ninth Street<BR>
Springfield, IL 62703<BR>
(217) 524-3300<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III. Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
415 Illinois Compiled Statutes 5/1 et. seq. (Illinois Environmental Protection Act)
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
35 Illinois Administrative Code 702, 704, 705, 730  
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV. 	Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A permit may be required to inject fluids into the ground from a Class V (shallow, non-hazardous-fluid) well. A permit is required for injections for Class I (deep injection wells ). Class II wells are regulated by Department of Natural Resources/Mines & Minerals. Office of Mines and Minerals.<P>

The Agency may give permission for the injection of fluids by either authorizing by rule based upon upon applicant's Inventory Report Form, or by issuing a Permit.<P>

A Permit authorizes activities including (but not limited to) deep well injection of hazardous-waste, other deep-well injection or shallow non-hazardous-waste disposal, biodremediation, injection of waste into underground formations, groundwater remediation projects and water recharge.<P>

A Permit is not required to apply nutrients onto the soil. Injecting fluid(s) without authorization by rule or a Permit, is subject to penalties including a jail term, and fines. Penalties vary with the severity and duration of the violation. Permits typically are valid for 5 years and may be renewed.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V. 	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must complete and file with the Agency an Inventory Report Form containing information that will allow the Agency to evaluate whether a Permit is required.  Applications to inject fluids into the ground from a Class V well must include a "Class V Inventory Form". Upon receipt of the Inventory Form, the Agency will determine if a Permit is necessary. If a Permit is not necessary, the operation is authorized by rule.  If a Permit is required, applicants must submit an "Underground Injection Control Permit Application Form" to the Agency. The average processing time for the "Underground Injection Control Permit Application Form" is 90 days for existing facilities and 180 days for new facilities. Denials are usually the result of technical deficiencies in the application. Denied applications may be appealed to the Agency.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI. 	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Approval is required from the local government where the proposed injection is located before a Permit will be issued, unless the injection is of private waste on a private site.  A permit may be required from IEPA's Bureau of Water, Bureau of Air, LUST Section (Leaking Underground Storage Tanks) or RCRA Unit (Resource Conservation Recovery Act). Inventory forms must be updated whenever the well changes. Permitees are required to seal the well. (IEPA recommends that permitees call the Illinois Department of Public Health when a well has been sealed.) <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII. Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
None.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

