<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: State Agency Historic Resources Protection Act</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.  Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
State Agency Historic Resources Protection Act
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Historic Preservation Agency<BR>
Old State Capitol<BR>
Springfield, IL 62701<BR>
Division of Preservation Services<BR>
(217) 785-5027<BR> 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
20 Illinois Compiled Statutes 3420
</DD></DL>

<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Title 17 Illinois Administrative Code, Chapter 6, Part 4180
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
This Act requires other state agencies to work in conjunction with IHPA in the issuance of licenses or awarding grants to businesses preparing to begin construction or development projects. The purpose of this Act is to safegard the historic resources of the State. Any agency granting a permit or awarding money for a project must determine whether the proposed project poses potential  harm to state historic resources. IHPA does not  issue an actual permit. IHPA approval in the form of a written "sign off" is required before the applicant can commence with the project. Non-compliance with this Act may result in a civil suit. 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
If a potential threat to a historic resource is determined to exist by a funding or licensing agency, the applicant should contact the IHPA and request review and approval. IHPA requires the applicant to submit a written description of the project.  The applicant must also include the name of the funding or licensing agency, a map showing the project location, current photos of all standing structures within the project area, the address of the project, and project plans and specifications.<P>

If the IHPA determines that the project does pose a threat to historic resources of the state, the funding or licensing agency will require the applicant to have a survey conducted to verify that no historical, architectural or archaeological resource will be harmed by the proposed project. IHPA has 30 days after being notified to review the proposed permit and make a determination on potential harm to historic resources. Denial of the permit or funding is usually due to harm that a project would cause to a historical resource. Appeal of a denied aplication may be made to the Director of the IHPA and the agency State agency reaching a compromise on how to alter the project to  preserve the historic resource.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-requisites, Co-requisites & Post-requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Businesses must submit to the IHPA a map of the site location, a brief project description and photographs of any structures on the property, where applicable.  
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
None.
</DD></DL>


<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
