<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Nurse Agency Licensing   </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.	Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Nurse Agency Licensing   
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.	Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Labor<BR>
Fair Labor Standards Division <BR>
Nurse Agency Section<BR>
Chicago, IL 60601<BR>
(312) 793-4463<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.	Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
225 Illinois Compiled Statutes 510/1 et seq.
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
68 Illinois Administrative Code, Sections 690.00 et seq.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV:	Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A Nurse Agency* may not be established, operated, maintained or advertised in Illinois until a license has been issued by the Department. <P>

A separate license is required for each location which is not owned & managed by the same individual, firm, corporation, partnership or legal entity. The requirements of this license applies most often to businesses commonly referred to as temporary staffing agencies, which employ, assign or refer RN's, LPN's or CNA's to health care facilities. Private duty nursing and home care are excluded from the requirements of this law. (An example of a  typical situation requiring this license:  A business that refers a Critical Care Registered Nurse to a hospital. The assignment may last as few as one or two weeks, or as long as six months.) Conducting such a business without a license may result in a $1,000 fine  per day. Licenses are valid for one year, unless suspended or revoked.<P>

*A Nurse Agency is a business that employees, assigns or refers RN's, LPN's, or certified nurse aides to what is defined as a health care facility in Section 3 of the Illinois Health Facilities Planning Act (including hospitals, nursing homes, ambulatory surgical treatment centers, dialysis centers, non-governmental HMO's) for a fee. <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must complete and file (notarized) Form  IL-452-0109.  <P>

Average processing time is 7 - 10 days. Causes for denial include failure to comply with minimum standards of Act or Rules and Regulations, conviction of an applicant of a felony, insufficient financial or other resources to operate the nurse agency, failure to establish appropriate personnel policies and procedures for selecting nurses and certified nurse aides. Denied applications may be appealed under the Administrative Review Law.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must provide proof of professional liability insurance in statutory amounts.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.	Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Application fee is $250.<P>
Annual Fee is $250.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
