<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Approval to Conduct Incidental Coal Extraction</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.   Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Approval to Conduct Incidental Coal Extraction
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Natural Resources<BR>
Office of Mines and Minerals<BR>
Land Reclamation Division<BR>
524 South Second Street<BR>
Springfield, IL 62701-1787<BR>
(217) 782-4970<BR>
TDD:  (217) 524-4626<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III. Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
225 Illinois Compiled Statutes 720 (Surface Coal Mining Land Conservation & Reclamation Act)
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
62 Illinois Administrative Code 1700-1850
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV. 	Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Approval of the OMM is required before extracting coal.<P>

However, any individual or business that extracts coal, incidental to the extraction of other minerals, where the coal extracted does not exceed 16 2/3% of the total mineral tonnage mined for purposes of commercial use or sale may obtain an exemption from specific permitting and performance standards by getting approval from the Office of Mines & Minerals (OMM). <P>

Failure to comply with the terms of the exemption shall subject the operator to direct enforcement action for violations of the coal regulatory program. <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must file an application to OMM (but should meet with the Agency at least 6 months prior to the expected application submittal date to discuss the application requirements). The application must establish that the amount of coal to be extracted will not exceed 16 2/3% of the total mineral tonnage mined and that the other minerals to be mined are to be used for commercial use or sale. A map of the mining area is required as well as a description of the mining and mineral processing activities and geologic information gathered from test borings on the area. After submitting the application, an applicant is required to place a local newspaper advertisement identifying the persons claiming exemption. This must also contain a description of the proposed operation and its location. Any potential adversely affected parties may submit written comments on the application to the Department. Within 30 days of the local newspaper advertisement OMM issues its written decision to issue or deny the exemption request. Any adversely affected party may request an administrative review.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
All coal mine sites are required to have a National Pollutant Discharge Elimination System permit from the Illinois EPA. Additional permits may be required from the Illinois Department of Natural Resources - Office of Water Resource Management, and the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers if floodplain disturbances are planned or if a large impoundment is proposed to be constructed. Permits or approvals from the federal Mine Safety & Health Administration (MSHA) will also be required. Operators must file an annual report with OMM detailing the annual production of coal and other minerals and the revenues derived from each. Sites are subject to inspections by OMM.  If an exemption is granted, annual reports must be submitted to OMM.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII. 	Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
None.
</DD></DL>


<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
