<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Permit to Conduct Coal Mining Operations</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.   Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Permit to Conduct Coal Mining Operations
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Natural Resources<BR>
Office of Mines & Minerals (OMM)<BR>
Land Reclamation Division<BR>
524 South Second Street<BR>
Springfield, IL 62701-1787<BR>
(217) 782-4970<BR>
TDD:  (217) 524-4626<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.	Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
225 Illinois Compiled Statutes 720 
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
62 Illinois Administrative Code 1700-1850
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV. 	Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A permit is required to extract coal, either by surface or underground methods, including removal of coal refuse. Exemptions from this requirement are as follows: 1) No permit is required where 250 tons or less of coal are removed in any 12 consecutive months for the  landowner's or lessee's own noncommercial use, or 2) where the extraction of coal incidental to the extraction of other minerals does not exceed 16 2/3% of the total tonnage mined for purposes of commercial use or sale.  However, where incidental extraction is proposed, the entity must first receive an exemption from the Department.  (This procedure is explained in a separate OMM Business Requirement Profile: "Approval to Conduct Incidental Coal Extraction".<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must file an application including background environmental data, legal information regarding an applicant's right to mine, any past violation history, corporate structure (if applicant is incorporated), maps and detailed engineering drawings prepared by, or under the direction of, and sealed by a qualified, registered professional engineer licensed in Illinois. <P>

Applicant is required to place a newspaper advertisement for 4 consecutive weeks, describing the type of proposed activity and location. Anyone who believes he or she may be adversely affected by the proposal may request a conference or hearing.  <P>

Based upon OMM's internal technical review, and comments received from the general public and Interagency Committee, a decision to approve, deny or modify the application is issued. (In nearly all cases, the Department issues a decision requiring the applicant to modify the application.) If the applicant responds positively to OMM's request for modifications a permit may be issued.  Generally, applications take 1-2 years to process. A permit may be denied to anyone "blocked" on the Applicant Violator System, a computer network of mine operators with compliance problems.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI. 	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
OMM may not issue a permit until an applicant posts a performance bond guaranteeing reclamation of the site. <P>

Coal mine sites require a National Pollutant Discharge Elimination System Permit from the Illinois EPA. Additional permits may be required from the Illinois Department of Natural Resources - Office of Water Resource Management, and the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers if floodplain disturbances are planned or if a large impoundment is proposed to be constructed, and the federal Mine Safety & Health Administration.  Operators are obligated to adhere to performance and monitoring requirements. <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII. Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
$125 per acre for all land within the permit boundary to be surface mined. $5 per acre for each year the bond is in force for all non-surface mined land within the permit boundary.<P>
</DD></DL>


<HR>
