<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Certificate of Approval for Microbiological Analyses of Samples from Public Water Supplies and their Sources</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.  Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Certificate of Approval for Microbiological Analyses of Samples from Public Water Supplies and their Sources
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Public Health<BR>
Office of Health Protection / Division of Laboratories <BR>
825 North Rutledge <BR>
Springfield, IL 62794<BR>
(217) 782-6562<BR>
TDD:  1-800-547-0466 (for hearing impaired use only)<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
415 Illinois Compiled Statutes 5/4  (Illinois Environmental Protection Act);<BR>
20 Illinois Compiled Statutes 2310/55.10;<BR>
20 Illinois Compiled Statutes 2310/55.11; Civil Administrative Code of Illinois<BR>
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
35 Illinois Administrative Code 183, Subpart C (Certification & Operation of Environmental Laboratories) (Joint Rules of the Illinois Environmental Protection Agency, the Illinois Department of Public Health, and the Illinois Department of Nuclear Safety)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
This Certificate is awarded to municipal, commercial and health department laboratories on the basis of their laboratory facilities, equipment, quality assurance records, and the performance of individual analysts performing microbiological tests for public water supplies and their sources.<P> 

To be certified, analysts must demonstrate an ability to properly perform representative test procedures with which he or she is involved while under observation of the certification officer.<P> 

A Certificate is valid for 2 years, but may be recalled if a laboratory fails to maintain eligibility standards.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must complete and file Personnel and Laboratory Information Forms with the Department.<P> 

The Department usually takes 90 days to review an application, then conducts an on-site evaluation before the laboratory may officially test water samples.  The Department schedules another on-site evaluation to be conducted before the expiration date of the Certificate.<P> 

The most common reasons for denial of an application are:  The inability of the analyst to perform procedures correctly during the on-site evaluation, malfunctioning equipment or inadequate records.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>  
<DL><DD>
Analysts must work under the direction of a laboratory supervisor who has at least a bachelor's degree in microbiology, biology, chemistry, or a closely related field.<P> 

The laboratory analyst must have a minimum of six months bench experience in a microbiological analytical laboratory.<P>
</DD></DL>  

<HR>
<H3>VII. Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
None.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
