<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Dairy Farms, Dairy/Milk Processing Plants & Milk Hauler/Sampler</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.   Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Dairy Farms, Dairy/Milk Processing Plants & Milk Hauler/Sampler
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.   Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Public Health<BR>
Division of Food, Drugs and Dairies / Office of Health Protection<BR>
Dairy Program<BR>
525 West Jefferson<BR>
Springfield, IL 62761<BR>
(217) 782-7532<BR>
TDD:  1-800-547-0466 (for hearing impaired use only)<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
410 Illinois Compiled Statutes 620/21.1 (Illinois Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act), and 635/1 (Grade A Pasteurized Milk and Milk Products Act).
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
77 Illinois Administrative Code 775 and 785.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Dairy farmers who produce and sell milk must obtain a Farm Permit from the Department. Farm Permits are valid until revoked.<P> 

Processors of milk or producers of dairy products (such as ice cream, cheese, yogurt, etc.), must obtain a Processing Plant Permit  Processing Plant Permits are valid for 1 year.  Out-of-state companies selling dairy products in Illinois also must obtain a Processing Plant Permit. These permits are valid for 1 year.<P> 

Transporting raw milk from a dairy farm to a processing plant requires a Milk Hauler/Sampler License. This license is valid for 1 year.<P>
</DD></DL>
<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Dairy Farms: Producers must complete and file a "Farm Approval Application". Upon receipt of the application the Department will conduct a field inspection of the milking facilities. If satisfactory the Department will issue a producer permit number assigned. Applications take 7-10 days to process.<P> 

License holders must maintain good sanitation, a clean environment and healthy animals.<P> 

Dairy/Milk Processing Plant:  Applicants must complete and file a "Processing Plant Application" together with a "Product Flow" blue-print with the Department. Upon receipt of the application the Department will conduct a field inspection. If satisfactory, the Department will issue a permit. Applications are processed within 7-10 days.<P>
 
License holders must maintain good sanitation, a clean environment and healthy animals.<P> 

Milk Hauler/ Sampler:  Those intending to transport raw milk from a dairy farm to a processing plant must submit an "Application to become a Milk Hauler/Sampler", and take and pass a Department examination.<P> 

Applications are processed within 1 week.<P> 

Vehicles used for transportation also must be inspected.<P> 

If the applicant passes the exam and the vehicle inspection is satisfactory, a permit is issued.<P> 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
None.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
<STRONG>Dairy Farm Permit:</STRONG>  None<P>	
<STRONG>Milk Hauler/Sampler:</STRONG>  $25 annual permit fee<P>
<STRONG>Dairy/Milk Processing Plant:</STRONG>  $100 annual permit fee<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
