<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Health Maintenance Organization (HMO)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.  Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Health Maintenance Organization (HMO)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Public Health<BR>
Office of Health Care Regulation / Division of Health<BR>
Facilities and Programs<BR>
525 West Jefferson<BR>
Springfield, IL 62761<BR>
(217) 782-7412<BR>
TDD:  1-800-547-0466 (for hearing impaired use only)<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
215 Illinois Compiled Statutes 125 (Health Maintenance Organization)
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
77 Illinois Administrative Code 240 (Minimum Health Care Standards for Health Maintenance Organization)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
No organization shall establish or operate a Health Maintenance Organization in Illinois without obtaining a certificate of authority from the Illinois Department of Insurance. Licensure rules include personnel requirements, provisions for care and medical records. Portions of the Insurance Code apply to HMOs.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
To receive a certificate of authority, the organization must submit to the Illinois Department of Insurance: a copy of the by-laws or other documents that describe the conduct of internal affairs; a list of responsible individuals within the organization; information related to premium rates or a formula basis for rates; financial statement;  proposed marketing plan; a description of  the geographic service area; a description of resolving enrollees grievances; a description of internal quality management, and; annually, an audited financial report. 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Examinations concerning the quality of health care services are conducted as IDPH deems necessary, but at least every year.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
There is an annual fee of $1,200, plus:  for the first 50,000 enrollees, $.03 per enrollee; for 50,000 to 100,000 enrollees, $.02 per enrollee, and; for more than 100,000, $.01 per enrollee.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
