<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Life Care Facilities Program</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.  Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Life Care Facilities Program
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Public Health<BR>
Office of Epidemiology and Health Systems Development<BR>
Division of Health Policy<BR>
525 West Jefferson<BR>
Springfield, IL 62761<BR>
(217) 782-6235<BR>
TDD:  1-800-547-0466 (for hearing impaired use only)<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
210 Illinois Compiled Statutes 40/1 et seq. (Illinois Life Care Facilities Act)
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
77 Illinois Administrative Code 396 (Life Care Facilities Contract Code)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A "Permit to Offer and Enter into Life Care Contracts" is required to enter into a contract to provide life care to their residents. Life care is the provision of nursing, medical or personal care services, and maintenance services, to a person, for a term over one year.<P> 

Entering into a contract to provide life care without a permit is a Class A misdemeanor.<P> 

Permits have an unlimited term, but are non-transferable.<P>  
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must file an "Application for Permit to Offer & Enter Into Life Care Contracts" with the Department, providing a copy of the proposed residency contract, a letter of credit or escrow agreement to fulfill Section 7 of the Act, and additional documentation, as required.<P>

Applications completely and correctly prepared are usually reviewed within 30 business days.<P>

A common reason for the denial of an application is that the facility does not meet the definition of Life Care Facility as required by the Act. The provisions of the Illinois Administrative Procedure Act and the Administrative Review Law apply.<P>

The facility is restricted to the number of living units stated on the Permit.  Changes in the number of living units require an additional application.<P> 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
The Permit holder is required to provide independently audited financial statements to the Department on a yearly basis. Any changes in financial condition or in the information reported in the initial application must be reported to the Department.<P> 

Permit holders are required to maintain an escrow agreement or letter of credit for the duration of any outstanding debt, to comply with Section 7 of the Act.<P>

Change of facility ownership requires an application for a new Permit.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
<STRONG>Permit application fee:</STRONG>  $100.
</DD></DL>


<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
