<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Pediatric Skilled Nursing Facility; Facilities for Individuals with Developmental Disabilities; Sheltered Care Facility; Skilled Nursing Facility & Intermediate Care Facility</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.  Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Pediatric Skilled Nursing Facility; Facilities for Individuals with Developmental Disabilities; Sheltered Care Facility; Skilled Nursing Facility & Intermediate Care Facility
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Public Health<BR>
Office of Health Care Regulation / Bureau of Long-Term Care<BR>
525 West Jefferson<BR>
Springfield, IL 62761<BR>
(217) 782-2913<BR>
TDD:  1-800-547-0466 (for hearing impaired use only)<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
210 Illinois Compiled Statutes 45 (Nursing Home Care Act). 
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
77 Illinois Administrative Code 390 (Long-Term Care for Under Age 22
Facilities Code)<BR>
77 Illinois Administrative Code 350 (Intermediate Care for the
Developmentally Disabled Facility Code)<BR>
77 Illinois Administrative Code 330 (Sheltered Care Facilities Code)<BR>
77 Illinois Administrative Code 300 (Skilled Nursing & Intermediate Care
Facilities Code)<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.   Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A license is required to open, establish, conduct or maintain a nursing home. License requirements involve issues such as administration, medical and dental care, nursing and personal care, medications and medication administration, resident and facility records, food service, housekeeping, laundry and maintenance; resident rights; and physical plant. Failure of license holders to comply with the Act are subject to fines up to $50,000, revocation of the license, assignment of a facility "monitor" to oversee operations or a  "receiver" to take over the facility, or issuance of a "conditional license".<P> 

Operating without a license may result in civil or criminal prosecution by the Attorney General. Licenses are valid for 6 months to 2 years. Most are valid for 1 year.<P>  
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.   Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must file a "Long Term Care Facilities License Application", together with information including a statement of ownership, the location of the facility, the number and type of residents, the experience and training of staff and a financial statement. License applications are usually processed within 1 month.<P> 

An application may be denied or a license revoked if the facility fails to comply with the Act and rules; refuses to allow an inspection; is operating or intends to operate with insufficient funds or staff; is not under the supervision of a licensed nursing home administrator; has violated resident rights; has submitted false information to the Department; or the licensee, applicant or person designated to operate the facility has been convicted of a felony or two or more crimes involving moral turpitude.<P> 

Facilities certified to participate in Medicare/Medicaid programs must satisfy federal standards.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
<STRONG>Pre-Requisite:</STRONG> A Certification of Need (CON) is required from the Illinois Health Facilities Planning Board for an applicant to be eligible.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Initial and annual fees are $200.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
