<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Private Sewage  (Installation Contractor License & Disposal System Pumping Contractor License)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.  Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Private Sewage  (Installation Contractor License & Disposal System Pumping Contractor License)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Public Health<BR>
Division of Environmental Health / Environmental Engineering Section<BR>
525 West Jefferson<BR>
Springfield, IL 62761<BR>
(217) 782-5830<BR>
TDD: 1-800-547-0466  (hearing impaired use only)<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
225 Illinois Compiled Statutes 225/1 (Private Sewage Disposal Licensing Act)
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
77 Illinois Administrative Code 905
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A private sewage disposal system  installation contractor license is required for persons in business to construct, install, modify, repair, maintain or service private sewage disposal systems.<P>

A private sewage disposal system pumping contractor license is required to clean or pump private sewage disposal systems or haul or dispose of wastes removed from a private sewage system.<P> 

Licenses are valid from January 1 to December 31st of each year.<P> 

Local health departments may license contractors in lieu of, or in addition to, the state Department's license.  Applicants should check with the local health department for license requirements.<P> 

Licenses expired for more than 3 years may be restored by passing a written examination and paying all lapsed fees plus a reinstatement fee.<P>

Performing private sewage disposal system work without a license is a Class A Misdemeanor.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must pass a written exam before submitting an "Application for Licensure as a Private Sewage Disposal System Installation Contractor" or an "Application for Licensure as a Private Sewage Disposal System Pumping Contractor" to the Department. 
Applications are usually processed in a week. 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Each year Private Sewage Disposal System Pumping Contractors must submit to the Department the locations and the number of gallons of septage disposed of.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
<STRONG>Examination fee:</STRONG> $25<P>

<STRONG>License and renewal fee:</STRONG> $50 per license. (Licensed plumbers are exempt from the fee.)<P>

<STRONG>Reinstatement of an expired license:</STRONG> $20 plus all lapsed renewal fees.<P>

Application fees must be submitted at least 30 days prior to the examination.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
