<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Illinois Notary Public Commissions</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.   Business Requirement Profile: </H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Notary Public Commissions
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Secretary of State<BR>
Index Department<BR>
111 East Monroe St.<BR>
Springfield, IL 62756<BR>
(217) 782-7017<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III. Statute:     </H3>  
<DL><DD>
5 Illinois Compiled Statutes 312
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV. Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A business may find it useful to retain a Notary Public commission for at least one employee for the execution of contracts and other legally enforceable documents.   A Notary Public may not notarize their own signature, so an employee should be commissioned who will not be the signatory to such transactions.<P>

To be eligible for a Notary Public commission, the applicant must have
resided in Illinois for 30 days preceding the application; be a U.S.
citizen or lawfully admitted alien; be at least 18 years old; be able to
read and write the English language; not have had their commission revoked
during the past 10 years; and not have been convicted of a felony.
Commissions are effective for 4 years.  Applications and Notary Public
Handbooks, which contain the Act, are available at the Index Department.  A
Notary Public must apply for a new commission in the event of a change in
name or county of residence.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
The applicant must file a signed and correctly notarized application, along with a $10 appointment fee, and a $5,000 Surety Bond.  The Index Department will process the application within two to three weeks.  Then the Department mails the commission to the county clerk's office to be recorded.  The county clerk will notify the applicant that the commission is at their office.  Upon payment of a $10 fee to the county clerk, the applicant may pick-up the commission or have it mailed.<P>

Failure to respond to the county clerk's notification within 60 days will
result in the commission being returned to the Secretary of State's office
for cancellation.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI. Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Notaries public must ensure that their notary stamps contain the commission expiration date on the official Secretary of State commission.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII. Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
There is a $10 application fee payable to the Secretary of State, and a $10 recording fee payable to the county clerk.
</DD></DL>


