<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- December 17, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
December 17, 1996<p>
1996 Outstanding Year for Film, Television Production in Illinois
</h3>

<strong>CHICAGO,  ILL.</strong>  --  Gov. Jim Edgar today announced that 27 film and television productions provided temporary jobs for more than 25,000 Illinois residents and pumped $100 million into the state's economy in 1996.<p>

"The Illinois film industry is thriving," the Governor said.  "We are seeing the results of the rebuilding efforts of the Illinois Film Office in film and television productions such as 'Chain Reaction,' 'A Thousand Acres," 'My Best Friend's Wedding,'  'ER,' 'Early Edition,' and 'Chicago Hope.'  Hollywood is investing in Illinois because of our willingness to accommodate the demands of the film marketplace and the excellent cooperation between labor unions and state and local governmental bodies to meet the industry's needs."<p>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior adviser for economic development, said the film industry makes a significant contribution to the state's economy.<p>

"This is only the second year in the 20-year history of the Illinois Film Office that revenue has reached $100 million in actual cash expenditures in Illinois," Kustra said.  "Since 1976, the motion picture and television industry has contributed more than $800 million to the state's economy and provided more than 250,000 temporary jobs."<p>

Some of the highlights of 1996 include "A Thousand Acres," filmed in Rochelle, Creston, and Mendota in September, and "35 Miles from Normal," filmed last summer in Pontiac.  Chicago productions include "Michael," due for release at Christmas; recently released "The Chamber." and 1997 releases such as "Love Jones," "Dogwater," "Hoods," "Reach the Rock," "Home Alone 3," and "My Best Friend's Wedding."<p>      

In addition to big Hollywood productions, which clearly boost the Illinois economy, the Illinois Film Office is seeing strong growth in independent film productions originating in Illinois, a major indicator of the future health of the local film industry.<p> 

The Illinois Film Office, a division of the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs, is responsible for attracting productions and promoting the film and television industry in Illinois.  Activities include location scouting, acting as a liaison between state and local governments, and providing information that outlines available film facilities and services, ranging from accountants to screenwriters.<p>

<center><strong>###</strong></center>
	 
