<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- December 17, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
December 17, 1996<p>
Governor Releases $1 Million in Emergency Heating Funds to Help Low-Income Families Re-Establish
Utilities Service
</h3>

<strong>SPRINGFIELD, ILL.</strong>  --  Gov. Jim Edgar today released $1 million in state emergency heating assistance to help low-income Illinois families and individuals re-establish utility services.<p>

"With the onset of frigid winter temperatures, thousands of Illinoisans who can't afford the cost of utilities may well find their lives threatened by the bitter cold," the Governor said.  "I have asked that state government tap all available resources to help low-income citizens currently without heat for their homes." <p>

The $1 million released today comes from the Low-Income Home Energy Assistance Program of the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs.  Nearly half -- about  $465,000 -- would go to residents of the City of Chicago and Cook County.  The rest will be distributed throughout the state to areas with the greatest need.<p>

Up to $500 a year in emergency funds is available to households that have had utilities disconnected or that fuel suppliers refuse to serve without immediate payment.  The funds also can be used to help pay for repair or replacement of heating systems that do not work.<p>

To qualify, applicants must show that they are low-income households and that they are responsible for the energy bill from the disconnected utility or fuel vendor.  They must also show they have paid at least 10 percent of the household's past 90-day income toward energy services.<p>

About 6,000 residents already have received emergency assistance through state and federal programs this year.  An additional 95,000 have received one-time payments toward their energy bills.<p>

Additional information about the program is available by calling DCCA's Energy Assistance Hotline toll-free at 800/252-8643.<p>

<center><strong>###</strong></center>
	 
