<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
October 16, 1996<p>
Governor Congratulates Eli's Cheesecake Co. on Opening of New Headquarters
</h3>

<strong>CHICAGO, ILL.</strong>  --  Gov. Jim Edgar today joined with business and civic leaders in Chicago to celebrate the grand opening of the new $9 million bakery and headquarters for Eli's  Cheesecake Co. in Chicago Industry-Tech Park on the city's northwest side.<p>
  	    
"This opening represents an economic development milestone for the city of Chicago and the State of Illinois," the Governor said.  "First, Eli's reputation is much of the reason people across the country think of Chicago and Illinois when they think of fine cheesecake, and this opening certainly reinforces that connection.  <p>

"But the opening also represents the first project in a plan to redevelop the former Chicago-Read Mental Health Center site.  That creates exciting new opportunities for businesses to relocate and grow within the city of Chicago at costs competitive with the surrounding suburbs.  Eli's is to be commended as the first company to recognize the potential of Industry-Tech Park with the opening of Eli's Cheesecake Co."<p>

The Edgar administration will provide Eli's with a $300,000 Small Business Development Loan for the project through the state Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA).<p>  

Eli's Chicago's Finest Cheesecake President Marc Schulman said his company is proud to open Eli's Cheesecake Co. in Chicago.<p>

"The support of the city and the state and the loyalty of our customers made possible the achievement of our dream to build a state-of-the-art facility," said Schulman.  "We appreciate the opportunity to relocate in our current neighborhood, and we have built a true showcase for food products made in Illinois."  <p>         

"Today's event is just the latest example of how our investments in revitalizing economic development throughout Illinois are benefitting our businesses and our citizens," Edgar said. <p> 

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior advisor for economic development, said the development of Industry-Tech Park is a true partnership.<p>

"Public and private interests at the state and local level have a stake in realizing our goal of developing Industry-Tech Park," Kustra said.  "With Eli's Cheesecake Co. as an anchor we will continue to work together to build on our initial success."<p>        	

Chicago Industry-Tech Park was formally created in June of 1995 when the state agreed to provide 73 acres of surplus land that was part of the Chicago-Read Mental Health Center campus.<p>        

The redevelopment project is expected to take six to eight years and yield 580,000 square feet for modern industrial facilities, including processing, light-manufacturing and assembly facilities.  When fully developed, DCCA has estimated the park will generate more than $36 million in retail sales, $2.6 million in net state revenues, $2.8 million net local taxes and $100 million in payroll earnings.<p>


<center><strong>###</strong></center>
	 
