<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- October 10, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
October 10, 1996<p>
Governor Commends International Partnership that Resulted in Reopening Sparta Printing Plant
</h3>

<strong>SPARTA, Ill.</strong> -- Gov. Jim Edgar today joined with community leaders, area residents and Mexican dignitaries in celebrating the re-opening of a printing plant that has employed thousands over the years in Sparta.<p>

"With the opening of Sparta International Printing Co. we congratulate a community and region that never lost hope despite the serious economic setback suffered early this year," the Governor said.  "We also pay tribute to our international partner in this endeavor, Grupa Serla of Mexico, which saw the wisdom in establishing a new printing firm here."<p>

Sparta International Printing Co. (SIPCO), a subsidiary of Grupa Serla, will employ 24 initially and as many as 200 within a year.  The printing plant formerly housed Spartan Printing Co. which went out of business in February after 47 years.  The shutdown put 850 employees out of work.<p>

SIPCO officials say they intend to hire as many dislocated Spartan workers as possible into the new jobs.<p>

The Governor joined other state officials, local leaders, plant workers, officials from Grupo Serla, and Mexico Consul Humberto Zamora-Trevino for the ceremony commemorating SIPCO's opening.<p>

Edgar commended the community for its efforts in finding a buyer for the idled plant.  "You never gave up," he said.  "My administration has bee there for you and, together with our friends at Grupa Serla, we got the job done."<p>

After the Spartan plant closed, the state made available $1 million in Job Training Partnership Act funds to help employees who lost their jobs.<p>

To help the new firm get started, the Edgar administration offered up to $360,000 in Industrial Training Program funds for worker training.  The administration also provided $500,000 in Community Development Assistance Program funds to the City of Sparta for infrastructure needs at the plant.<p>

"Things looked bleak last winter, but this opening represents a solid beginning on the long road back," Edgar said.  "We owe a lot to the opportunities presented by the NAFTA agreement in 1993.  NAFTA made the result we see here today possible.  We've heard concerns about jobs leaving the United States.  Here's the reality:  A Mexican firm reopens an Illinois plant, hires Illinois workers and looks forward to years of growth.  That's real progress."<p>


<center><strong>###</strong></center>
	 
