<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- October 1, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
October 1, 1996<p>
DCCA Sponsors Events to Celebrate Illinois Recycling Day
</h3>

<strong>SPRINGFIELD, ILL.</strong> --  The Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) is sponsoring events in West Peoria and Genoa to celebrate Illinois Recycling Day, October 1, 1996.<p>

"Illinois is proud of its many outstanding recycling programs," said DCCA Director Dennis Whetstone.  "Our efforts to reduce waste and encourage recycling in our homes, schools, offices and factories are increasingly successful, as these events demonstrate.  Illinois Recycling Day is another opportunity to highlight state programs aimed at producing a better environment for all Illinois citizens."<p>

In West Peoria, a ribbon cutting ceremony is scheduled to kick-off West Peoria's new curbside recycling program.  The City of West Peoria, Illinois' newest municipality, used an $18,000 DCCA grant to purchase recycling bins and to support the project's educational and promotional efforts.  The bi-weekly program will provide all residents of West Peoria the opportunity to recycle a full spectrum of recyclable commodities, including newspaper, plastics, glass and metals.<p>

In Genoa, a ribbon cutting and dedication ceremony is planned at Pace Mat, Inc., a scrap tire-derived material mat production facility.  Pace Mat received a $500,000 DCCA grant to purchase hydraulic presses, tool and die equipment and other related equipment to produce scrap tire-derived mats and mat type products, including gymnasium mats and noise reduction flooring.  Pace Mat has matched DCCA's grant with more than $1.2 million worth of related equipment, engineering and design work and cash.<p>

"The market for recycled products is growing," said Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, Governor Jim Edgar's senior advisor for economic development.  "State government will continue to work with the recycling industry to develop innovative new ways to meet consumer demand, and at the same time improve the environment for our citizens."<p>

As the lead agency charged with supporting waste reduction and recycling efforts in Illinois, DCCA administers a variety of waste management programs, including the Materials Recycling Grants Program, the Used Tire Recovery Program and School Recycling Grants Program.  For more information on recycling programs, call DCCA at 217/785-2800 (TDD users call 217/785-0211).<p>

<center><strong>###</strong></center>
	 
