<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- August 22, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
August 22, 1996<p>
Governor Visits Excel Railcar; Notes NAFTA's Benefits to Company
</h3>

<strong>KENNEY, Ill.</strong> -- Gov. Jim Edgar today commended Excel Railcar Corporation on its success in promoting trade between Illinois and Mexico.  The company, one of the fastest-growing Hispanic companies in the U.S., has been a strong supporter of the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA).<p>

On a tour of the firm's plant in Kenney today, the Governor also announced new agreements the firm has signed, which will enable Excel to begin exporting Illinois grain and grain products to Mexico next year.<p>

"In supporting passage of the North American Free Trade Agreement, we were convinced that the agreement would be important, not just for large exporters, but also for small businesses like Excel Railcar Corporation," the Governor said.  "Excel's experience has shown that our convictions were right on target.  The company is one of our state's most enthusiastic partners as we promote trade between Illinois and Mexico. <p>

"Illinois offers a wide range of personalized assistance to help companies develop their export potential.  From one-on-one assistance through our network of International Trade Centers and NAFTA Opportunity Centers, to participation in trade and catalog shows and trade missions coordinated through our International Business Division and its foreign offices, Illinois is linking businesses with the resources they need to become successful in the global marketplace."<p>
 
Eugene Constance, President of Excel Railcar Corporation, often serves as a consultant to other small businesses entering the Mexican marketplace.  Constance said the state has been instrumental in helping his company broaden trade relationships. 	<p>

"I had the privilege of attending a trade mission to Mexico with Governor Edgar in March," he said.  "The contacts I made during that trade mission have already resulted in inquiries from Mexican companies and other U.S. firms, particularly Illinois firms, that have an interest in exporting to Mexico.  The state's trade office in Mexico City also has been extremely helpful.  Its director, Raymundo Flores, truly has a finger on the pulse of the business climate in Mexico."<p>

Excel Railcar Corporation, headquartered in Naperville, was founded in 1980 to provide railcars on full-service leases for the U.S., Canadian and Mexican markets.  Since then, the company has leased more than 1,500 new and refurbished railcars to companies using them for international service between the U.S. and Mexico.  Its Mexican customers include Cemex (cement), Vitro (glass) and Apasco (cement).  Excel this year also entered the U.S. railcar leasing market.  <p>

Growth led Excel to reactivate its railcar repair facility at Kenney in 1995, enabling the company to refurbish and repair its own fleet and other railcars.  The Kenney plant employs seven and expects to expand to 15 employees in late 1997.  Excel also employs 14 at its Mexico City subsidiary.<p>

<center><strong>###</strong></center>
	 
