Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
July 19, 1996<p>
</h3>

<H3 align=center>GOVERNOR AWARDS GRANTS TO ASSIST HOMELESS ILLINOISANS</H3>

<STRONG>SPRINGFIELD, IL</STRONG> -- Gov. Jim Edgar today announced nearly $1.7 million in grants to assist 50 not-for-profit organizations in 34 communities in providing emergency assistance to homeless people.<P>

"Homelessness is a tragedy that exists in both urban and rural areas," the Governor said.  "We are fortunate to have a number of excellent organizations that provide homeless people with both temporary shelter and services that can help them become self-sufficient.  These grants will help many of the organizations continue to provide these valuable services."<P>

A Hillsboro project is an example.  A Salvation Army survey of agencies and law enforcement officials in Montgomery County found nearly 275 cases of domestic violence had been reported, and more than 300 orders of protection filed during 1995.  The closest available shelter for victims of domestic violence is more than 50 miles away.  The Salvation Army will receive a $73,799 grant to assist in renovating the second floor of its building in Hillsboro to serve as a shelter facility for victims of domestic violence.	<P>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior adviser on economic development, said the grants were awarded through the Emergency Shelter Grants Program, administered by the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA).<P>

"Without these grants, many facilities would find it difficult to provide services," Kustra said.  "The grants not only help with essential operating costs, but also help underwrite some of the expenses for food, transportation and medicine, as well as programs designed to help homeless people identify and address their problems."<P>

Federally-funded through the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD), the Emergency Shelter Grants Program provides funding for projects that help homeless people in communities outside Cook County.  Grants are awarded on a competitive basis to projects that demonstrate clear need, an immediate ability to utilize the grant, and complement existing homeless shelter activities.  The maximum grant is $75,000 and must be matched by an equal amount from other sources.<P>

A list of grantees is attached.<P>


