<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- June 10, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
June 10, 1996<p>
Governor Joins in Groundbreaking for $37.5 Million SuperValu Distribution Center
</h3>

     <strong>OGLESBY, Ill.</strong> -- Gov. Jim Edgar today joined company and local officials in breaking ground for a $37.5 million Supervalu Inc. regional distribution center in Oglesby, serving a dozen states and creating more than 275 new jobs.<p>

     "This project is a terrific example of the economic development potential of Illinois' smaller communities," the Governor said.  "Our central location, high-quality transportation system and commitment to investing in infrastructure improvements continue to be major factors in attracting distribution centers and other facilities to Illinois. <p>

     "Supervalu expects to become the largest employer in the Oglesby area, with the likelihood of additional expansion.  State and local officials worked closely with this company to give Oglesby and the entire Illinois River Valley a significant economic boost."<p>

     Plans call for the 308,000 square-foot facility in LaSalle County to distribute more than 11,400 general merchandise and health and beauty care items to 1,500 stores in 12 states served by Minneapolis-based Supervalu, a leading food distribution company and the nation's 14th largest food retailer.<p>

     Jeff Noddle, President and Chief Operating Officer of Supervalu's wholesale food companies, said the new facility is an essential component in the company's plans for the future.  <p>

     "Supervalu's new multi-tiered distribution network will make major changes in the way food is distributed to our customers, and we believe ultimately this will have an effect on food distribution in this country," Noddle said.  "Today we celebrate the realization of many hours of hard work and much support from the State of Illinois, Oglesby Mayor Greg Cullinan, and many other representatives of Oglesby."<p>

     Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior advisor on economic development, said the resources of the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) and the Illinois Department of Transportation (IDOT) were tapped to assist in the project.<p>

     "Our assistance with these infrastructure improvements was one of the key factors in bringing Oglesby and Supervalu together," Kustra said.  "Sanitary sewer, water main and roadway improvements are required to build and operate this facility."<p>

     DCCA will award the City of Oglesby a $500,000 Community Development Assistance Program (CDAP) grant to help fund the improvements.  <p>

     The Illinois Department of Transportation has committed $1.2 million in Economic Development Funds toward the cost of improving County Highway 23 and Mallick Road that will provide access to the Supervalu facility.<p>

     The roadwork includes intersection improvements at County Highway 23 and Mallick, new traffic signals and drainage work along Mallick Road.  In addition, a Tax Increment Financing District was created at the local level to facilitate the project.<p>

     The Midwest distribution center is the second of three Supervalu regional distribution facilities to be developed as part of the company's strategic reinvention, a multi-year process called ADVANTAGE from Supervalu.<p>

     Construction on the Oglesby site will begin immediately.  The company expects to begin shipping from the new facility in early 1998.<p>


<HR>
