<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- May 9, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
May 9, 1996<p>
Governor Joins in Opening of New Ameritech Cellular Services Facility
</h3>

<em>RANTOUL, IL</em> - Gov. Jim Edgar today joined in ceremonies marking the official opening of a $2 million Ameritech Cellular Services call center at the former Chanute Air Base in Rantoul that is expected to create as many as 200 new jobs.<p>

"This facility is another milestone in Chanute's economic comeback," the Governor said.  "Working as a team, we have made aggressive efforts at the state and local levels to market the redevelopment potentials of Chanute, and those efforts are being rewarded with the creation of new jobs.<p>

"Ameritech has also cited the quality of the workforce in the Rantoul area as one reason it chose to locate here.  I am delighted that a company with Ameritech's record of excellence in customer service has given central Illinois worker such a strong vote of confidence."<p>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior advisor for economic development, said the opening of the Ameritech facility is another indicator of the healthy economic climate in Illinois.<p>

"Ameritech has recognized our efforts to make Illinois a great place to do business for their company, and for the increasing number of companies which rely on access to state-of-the-art communications technology," Kustra said.  "Our strong economy has helped companies such as Ameritech market their products to Illinois customers, which in turn has produced the need for expansion, and new job opportunities for our citizens."<p>

Explosive growth in the number of cellular and paging customer s in central Illinois prompted Ameritech Cellular Services to search for a site for the call center.  Chanute's 90,000 square foot former weather training facility underwent extensive renovation to create the new center.<p>

"Rantoul is thrilled with Ameritech's investment at the Aviation Center," said Rantoul Mayor Katy Podagrosi.  "I hope that Ameritech Cellular continues its growth here and throughout the region."<p>

The center is expected to provide 150 jobs by the end of 1997, and eventually in expected to employ as many as 200 people.<p>

"Ameritech's growth and investment in Rantoul reflects the leadership of Gov. Edgar and the General Assembly in developing a fully open and competitive telecommunications marketplace," said Doug Whitley, president of Ameritech Illinois.<p>

"Ameritech commends that leadership and the investment that the state itself is making to help train our expanding work force in Rantoul."<p>

The Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) will provide up to $210,000 in worker training funds through the Industrial Training Program (ITP).<p>

Responding to billing inquiries and fulfilling customer requests such as the addition of new cellular features are among the services to be provided by Ameritech paging and cellular associates.  Requests from central Illinois customer were previously routed to operations in Chicago.<p>


