<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- March 25, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
March 25, 1996<p>
Governor Edgar and Mayor Daley Announce the Second Illinois/Chicago Screenwriting Competition
</h3>

<em>CHICAGO, ILL.</em> -  Governor Jim Edgar and Mayor Richard M. Daley today announced that entries are currently being accepted for the second Illinois/Chicago Screenwriting Competition, sponsored by the Illinois Film Office and the Chicago Film Office.<p>

"After the successful launch of the first script competition we are thrilled to offer this opportunity once again to all our Illinois writers," the Governor said.  "An added bonus," adds Ron VerKuilen, Director of the Illinois Film Office, "is that the competition reaches out to a previously ignored sector of the film industry and allows them to become a part of our film community."<p>

The competition, open exclusively to residents of Illinois, is intended to support and encourage Illinois and Chicago-based writers by providing them with the opportunity to present their work to executives in the Los Angeles motion picture industry.<p>

"While providing a way for aspiring young screenwriters to get the attention they deserve, we are also nurturing Chicago's increasing and important role in the filmmaking industry that brings in thousands of jobs and millions of dollars to Chicago every year," said Mayor Richard M. Daley.<p>

The new director of the Chicago Film Office, Richard Moskal, added "There is nothing more important to the vitality of our community than nurturing and exposing the local talent.  It all begins with the writers."<p>

Entries will be judged through a jury system comprised of local film industry representatives and current or former Chicagoans who have written, directed or produced feature films.  All writers will receive a copy of their script's evaluations.  The winning scripts will be sent to major studios and production companies in Los Angeles.<p>

This year's competition will require a $25 application fee per script.  The fee will help underwrite the cost of the competition and award money.  The deadline for entries to the Illinois/Chicago Screenwriting Competition is June 7, 1996.  Interested writer may call (312)814-8711; TDD (800)419-0667 to receive an application.<p>

<h4>Illinois/Chicago Screenwriting Competition Rules and Regulations</h4>

<ul type=square>
<li>The competition is open ONLY to residents of the State of Illinois.
<li>There is a $25 nonrefundable fee per script to enter.  Unacceptable scripts will be returned along with the entry fee.  <li>Checks and money orders should be made payable to: Illinois/Chicago Screenwriting Competition.  DO NOT SEND CASH. * <li>Screenplays must have, or have pending, a U.S. copyright (contact 202-707-3000 to secure) and/or a Writer's Guild of America (WGA) registration (to secure, call 310-550-1000 for the West Coast office or 212-757-4360 for the East Coast office).
<li>Screenplays submitted must be original work.  Adaptations are not acceptable.
<li>No television pilots, episodes, specials, documentaries, music videos, novels, story treatment, etc. will be eligible.
<li>Collaborative screenplays will be accepted.  One person should be designated as the contact.
<li>Screenplays previously entered in other competitions are eligible.
<li>Screenplays only of standard and acceptable feature film length (100-125 pages) and format will be accepted.
<li>Screenplays must be set in Illinois with at least 75% of the script identifiably set within the state.
<li>There is no limit to the number of screenplays submitted.
<li>Screenplays must be postmarked by Friday, June7, 1996, or delivered to:<br>
Illinois/Chicago Screenwriting Competition<br>
One North LaSalle, Suite 2165<br>
Chicago, IL 60602<br>
<li>Accepted screenplays will not be returned.

</ul>

Eligible applicants must submit the following for EACH screenplay entry:<p>

1. Two copies of screenplay - Author identification must not appear in the text of the screenplay.<br>
2. Entry Form<br>
3. Signed Release Form<br>
4. A photocopy of valid Illinois Driver's License or ID Card.<p>


