<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: 1996 News Release -- February 8, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3><center>
February 8, 1996<p>
GOVERNOR APPROVES U.I. TAX CUT FOR BUSINESS
</center></h3>

<strong>SPRINGFIELD, ILL.</strong> -- Gov. Jim Edgar today signed legislation he called for in his State of the State message to help spur business growth and expansion through a $128 million cut in unemployment insurance taxes.<p>

"Coupled with an automatic $123 million reduction through the existing tax rate formula, this legislation means a savings of a quarter billion dollars this year for Illinois business," the Governor said.  "That money can bolster business growth and expansion rather than sitting idle in a government trust account."<p>

Illinois employers will save an average of 18 percent on their 1996 unemployment insurance tax bills because of the reduced rates.<p>

"With the state's unemployment levels at a 21-year low, we had fewer unemployment insurance claims, leaving a higher-than-expected balance in the U.I. trust fund, "Edgar said.  "This legislation strengthens our economy and gives Illinois employers a competitive edge -- without jeopardizing the fund or benefits for the unemployed."<p>

The year-end trust fund balance was $1.6 billion, $600 million higher than projected in 1992, based on a consensus of economic forecasts.  Unemployment insurance taxes are collected quarterly from employers and deposited in the fund, which can only be used to pay benefits to unemployed workers.<p>

"We will begin immediately to process the new tax rates, and statements will be mailed to all Illinois employers before the end of the month, " said Lynn Q. Doherty, Director of the Illinois Department of Employment Security.  "The new rates apply for the entire year of 1996."<p>

Under the legislation, the minimum rate is decreased to 0.5 percent from 0.6 percent, and the maximum rate drops to 6.8 percent form 8.2 percent.  The rate applies to the first $9,000 in annual wages paid to an employee.<p>

The legislation is effective immediately.<p>

Chief Sponsors of the measure, House Bill 1740, were Reps. Terry Parke (R-Hoffman Estates), Verna Clayton (R-Buffalo Grove), Bernard Pedersen (R-Palatine) and Ann Hughes (R-Woodstock)  and Sens. Chris Lauzen (R-Aurora), Dave Syverson (R-Rockford), Martin Butler (R-Park Ridge), Dick Klemm (R-Crystal Lake) and Dan Cronin (R-Elmhurst).<p>


