<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: 1996 News Release -- February 2, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3><center>
February 2, 1996<p>
GOVERNOR TARGETS HEATING ASSISTANCE FUNDS TO EMERGENCY RECONNECTIONS DURING FRIGID WEATHER
</center></h3>

<strong>CHICAGO, ILL.</strong> -- Gov. Jim Edgar today ordered that $5.2 million in heating assistance funds be targeted toward re-establishing utility service for low-income Illinois households that are currently without heat.<p>

"This week's record-setting bitter cold has dramatically heightened the urgent need for emergency heating assistance," the Governor said.  "For those with no utility service, the frigid weather is life-threatening.  Our immediate priority must be to reconnect low-income residents who do not have the financial means to re-establish electrical and heating service on their own.<p>

"I have directed the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) to work with local organizations to meet the current demand for emergency services before making funds available for other forms of assistance."<p>

Of the $5.2 million in Low-Income Energy Assistance Program (LIHEAP) funds released Thursday by the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, $1.8 million will be allocated to the City of Chicago.  The remainder of the funds will be distributed throughout the state on the basis of population, poverty, heating degree days and fuel costs.<p>

"Emergency assistance is available to eligible households that are disconnected from their primary and/or secondary utilities, or where a supplier has refused to deliver fuel without immediate payment," Edgar said.  "This assistance may also be available to help households with repair or replacement of inoperable heating systems."<p>

The amount of emergency assistance is the minimum amount necessary for reconnection of energy services.  Emergency assistance payments may not exceed a total of $500 per year per household, and eligible households are limited to one emergency assistance payment for the primary energy source and one for the secondary energy source.<p>

Applicants must prove that they are low-income, responsible for the energy bill from the disconnected utility or the delivered fuel vendor and have made a "good-faith effort" to maintain their energy services.  A good-faith effort is defined as having paid at least 10 percent of the household's past 90-day income toward energy services.<p>

LIHEAP funds may also be used to provide a one-time payment to utilities on behalf of eligible households.  The payment is applied toward a participant's energy bill.<p>

Including the $5.2 million, Illinois has received $50.2 million in federal LIHEAP funding to assist low-income residents during the current winter.  Approximately 7,000 residents have already received emergency assistance.  An additional 140-,000 have received energy assistance.<p>

Even with the addition of the latest round of funding, the federal government has provided only two-thirds of last year's funding, when $74.7 million was used to assist 13,000 residents with emergency reconnection assistance and 210,000 residents with energy assistance.<p>

For information about the program, residents may call DCCA's Energy Assistance Hotline at 800/252-8643 or 800/419-0667 (TDD).<p>


