<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3><center>January 2, 1996</center></h3>

<h3 align=center>SMALL BUSINESSES URGED TO UTILIZE ENVIRONMENTAL ASSISTANCE PROGRAM</h3>

<strong>SPRINGFIELD, ILL.</strong> -- Gov. Jim Edgar today announced that the Illinois Small Business Environmental Assistance Program, administered by the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA), helped more than 1,200 small businesses comply with rules and regulation of the 1990 Clean Air Act Amendments during its first year.<p>

"This program has been extremely successful in helping small business owners navigate the environmental regulatory process without the fear of regulatory action," the Governor said.  "As the state's business advocate, DCCA is in a unique position to provide these companies with the answers to their environmental questions."<p>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior economic development advisor, urges small companies to call the Illinois Environmental Assistance Helpline.  Callers to the helpline, 800/252-3900 (TDD) 800/785-6055, can get answers to a variety of questions and concerns.<p>

"Action by the federal government has brought more small businesses into the regulatory process than ever before," Kustra said.  "I encourage anyone who operates a small business in Illinois to take advantage of the free and confidential services this special helpline offers."<p>

The program also offers an environmental clearinghouse of more than 300 publications that include information on rules, fact sheets, environmental service companies in Illinois and How to select an environmental consultant.<p>

