<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- December 20, 1995</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
December 20, 1995<p>
  Governor Applauds $38 Million Deere Development Project                  
</h3>





<EM>MOLINE, ILL</EM>. - Gov. Jim Edgar today joined local officials in announcing a $38 million development project that will create 260 jobs in the Quad-Cities area and rejuvenate Moline's downtown area with the headquarters for John Deere Health Care.<P>

"This development project will pump millions of dollars into the Quad-Cities economy," the Governor said.  "The jobs to be created will provide opportunities for area citizens in field ranging from health care administration to retail, hotel and restaurant management.<P>

"There was intense competition from other states for the centerpiece of this development, the headquarters for John Deere Health Care, but this fast-growing corporation preferred to stay in Illinois.  Our willingness to make the needed investments in infrastructure improvements and worker training to help the Illinois economy grow has once again made the difference.  We are proving yet again that Illinois is a good place to do business."<P>

Richard Van Bell, President of John Deere Health Care, said the company was pleased to be located in a state with progressive job training programs for its citizens.<P>

"We commend Governor Edgar and the State of Illinois for supporting this project, which is an example of what government can do for the common benefit of its people," Van Bell said.  "This is a cost-effective way to upgrade the skills of our employees, which will improve their service and productivity, therefore having a strong impact not only on John Deere Health Care, but also our community and the state of Illinois."<P>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior advisor for economic development, said there was outstanding community cooperation in bringing the project together.<P>

"The public/private partnership we have seen demonstrated in pulling this complicated project together is a tribute to the leadership of those involved," Kustra said.  "All of the components in the development fit together to produce a complex that will create jobs and spur economic development."<P>

The development plan calls for the construction of a 100,000-square-foot building to serve as John Deere Health Care's corporate headquarters.  It will house 300 current employees, as well as another 100 employees to be added later.<P>

Another 160 jobs created by the development will be in the tourism-driven retail, hospitality and restaurant industries.<P>
	
Adjacent to the office building will be a 15,000-square-foot John Deere Visitor Pavilion that will serve as a destination point for the company's out-of-town visitors.  The pavilion will feature displays and historic exhibits and is expected eventually to draw up to 400,00 visitors.<P>

The development also includes a new Community Transportation Center that will serve as an intercity bus transfer center and a staging area for bus tour groups.  A first-class hotel is also planned to accommodate overnight visitors to the downtown area.<P>

The City of Moline, the Rock Island County Metropolitan Transit District, Renew Moline and the Quad Cities Civic Center Authority are all committing substantial resources to allow the development plan to move forward.<P>

The State of Illinois is providing more than $1 million toward the project, including a $600,000 loan to the City of Moline through the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs' public infrastructure program.  Up to $300,000 in job training funds also will be allocated over three years to assist John Deere Health Care with Worker training.  In addition, DCCA also has approved a $100,000 tourism attraction program grant for the program to rejuvenate the downtown area.<P>

The Illinois Department of Transportation also is expected to provide assistance for infrastructure improvements at the Arsenal Island Bridge to accommodate traffic flow and increased demand for parking. <P>
 
<HR>
