<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
October 25, 1995<p>
Illinois Communities Awarded Grants to Upgrade Public Water and Sewer Systems                    
</h3>





<EM>SPRINGFIELD, ILL</EM>. - Gov. Jim Edgar today announced 87 communities throughout Illinois will share more than $22.6 million in Community Development Assistance Program (CDAP) grants to help fund improvements to local water and sewer systems.<P>

"Public health and safety, and the potential for economic growth, depend on our ability to maintain adequate public infrastructure systems," the Governor said.  "My Administration has made infrastructure improvement one of the cornerstones of Illinois's' overall economic development policy.  These grants will provide cities and towns with the financial tools to make much-needed improvements.<P>

Edgar said a project in Fulton County is an example.<P>

Boil orders are often issued in the city of Farmington because of severely encrusted watermains that frequently break or lose pressure.  Farmington will receive a $350,000 grant combined with city funds to make the necessary water system improvements including replacement of water mains and construction of a new water tower.<P>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior advisor for economic development, said growth in rural areas depends in part on maintaining Illinois' high standards for public infrastructure.<P>

"Adequate water and sewage treatment systems are an important selling point for communities hoping to attract new economic development to their areas," Kustra said.  "Assisting local governments in making these improvements is a sound investment in the future of our state."<P>

CDAP grants are funded with federal block grant funds form the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD).  They are awarded by Department of Commerce and Community Affairs to units of local government with populations of 50,000 or less that are not located within one of the six large urban counties that receive funds directly from HUD.<P>

The maximum grant available is $400,000.  At least 51 percent of the project's beneficiaries must be people with low or moderate incomes.<P>

A list of the communities receiving CDAP public facilities and design engineering grants may be obtained by calling 217/785-6142. (TDD 800/785-6055).<P>
 
