<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- July 24, 1995</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
July 24, 1995<p>
Hoopeston Foods Acquires Pillsbury Plant; Project Will Retain 50 Jobs in Vermillion County                    
</h3>




<EM>SPRINGFIELD, ILL</EM>. - Gov. Jim Edgar today congratulated company officials on the announcement that Hoopeston Foods, Inc. will purchase the Pillsbury plant in Hoopeston, retaining 50 jobs with plans for further growth in the future.<P>

"The City of Hoopeston has a long and proud tradition in the food processing industry," the Governor said.  "When Pillsbury announced plans earlier this year to close its Hoopeston plant, we began working with local officials and economic developers to find a buyer for the facility.  Thanks to this close cooperation, coupled with innovative programs from both the state and community, Hoopeston Foods will keep the food processing tradition alive in Hoopeston."<P>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior economic development adviser, said the project was made possible inpart by a $650,000 Participation Loan provided by the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA).<P>

"This program enables the state to work with private lenders to make capital available to businesses like Hoopeston Foods that are creating and retaining jobs in our state," Kustra said.  "Our funds made it possible for the company to obtain conventional financing at a rate favorable enough to make the project feasible."<P>

The company will also receive a $100,000 participation loan from the Vermilion county Community Development Corporation, and a $100,000 loan form the city's revolving loan fund.  American National Bank and Trust, Chicago is the primary lender.<P>

John Steele, Hoopeston Foods, Inc. President, said the state and local support was critical to the project.<P>

"Financing of this project would not have been possible without a great deal of state and local assistance," Steele said.  "It has been a true public-private partnership to retain and grow a long-standing business in this community."<P>

Steele also thanked Hoopeston Mayor Robert Ault and the Hoopeston City Council, and Vicki Stewart of the Danville Area Economic Development corporation for their Assistance with the project.  Stewart, who said the state's involvement with the project was responsible for retaining invaluable manufacturing jobs for the Hoopeston community, commended Senator Harry "Babe" Woodyard and Representative William B. Black for their support.<P>

Hoopeston Foods, Inc. plans to establish a core business canning and labeling private-label dry-pack beans.  The company also plans to expand into a variety of food categories to complement its core product offering.<P>



