<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: DCCA News, January 1997</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#004080">

<HR>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/dcca/graph/dnews.gif" WIDTH=414 HEIGHT=127 alt="DCCA News"></CENTER>
<h2 align=center>January, 1997</h2>
<HR>

<h3>AMERICORPS--HELPING PEOPLE HELP THEMSELVES</h3>
<h4>by Curt Farrar, DCCA Division of Economic Opportunity</h4>

AmeriCorps, a national service initiative administered in Illinois by DCCA's Division of Economic Opportunity, is much more than just another service program.  It's a movement that unites diverse Illinoisans in efforts to improve neighborhoods and the quality of life for their residents.<p> 

AmeriCorps seeks to strengthen communities by providing manpower to help meet local educational, human, environmental and public safety needs, particularly those affecting children and young people.  Programs selected for funding recruit and train individuals who are willing to devote at least one year to serving as AmeriCorps members.<p>

Non-profit organizations, units of local government, state agencies, institutions of higher education or partnerships among such organizations are eligible for AmeriCorps participation.  Organizations submit proposals, which are reviewed by the 25-member bi-partisan Illinois Commission on Community Service (ICCS) and then sent for final approval and funding to the federal Corporation for National Service.  Successful proposals outline ways to meet identified needs, develop capacity by involving community volunteers, and have measurable outcomes to benefit the community.<p>

Organizations may apply for one of three different types of grants.  Planning grants provide organizations with up to $35,000 to plan an operational program.  Operating grants require a program design using 10 to 20 members and include funding for member support costs, staff salaries and administration.  The average size of operating grants is $250,000.  Education grants include awards for post-service education.<p> 

Participating organizations must operate an AmeriCorps-type program and bear total cost for the program.  This includes modest living allowances and health coverage for volunteers participating in the program.  Volunteers come from all ages and backgrounds.  After completing a year of service (at least 1,700 hours), AmeriCorps volunteer members receive an education award of $4,725 which can be used to help pay off student loans or finance college, graduate school, or vocational training. <p>
 
To date, ICCS has awarded more than $3 million to 13 grantees to develop programs through non-profit and state government agencies.  More than 300 people have been employed as AmeriCorps members throughout Illinois.  These volunteers have renovated 12 homes, tutored 1,500 children, cleaned five Illinois streams, trained 44,000 people in health and  safety, provided 4,000 day care referrals, and delivered case management and assistance to more than 200 homeless individuals.<p>

The ICCS has been assured that funds will be available for AmeriCorps operational grants for the 1997-98 program year.  For further information about AmeriCorps, contact the Illinois Commission on Community Service at 800/592-9896 (TDD users call 800/419-0667).<p>

<h4 align=center>###</h4>

<hr>
<h3>MARK YOUR CALENDARS!</h3>

The Illinois Institute for Rural Affairs, in conjunction with Rural Partners, will host the Eighth Annual Rural Community Economic Development Conference at the Holiday Inn East in Springfield, March 5 through March 6.  The conference will provide a broad overview of rural development issues and feature workshops on innovative economic development activities within rural Illinois.  For information, contact the Illinois Institute for Rural Affairs at Western Illinois University, 518 Stipes Hall, One University Circle, Macomb, IL  61455.<p> 

<h4 align=center>###</h4>

<hr>
<h3>TRAVEL INDUSTRY IS KEY TO THE ILLINOIS ECONOMY</h3>

The Illinois travel industry is flexing its muscles.  Recently, DCCA's Illinois Bureau of Tourism reported that the growth rate of Illinois tourism matched or exceeded the U.S. growth rate for the 13th consecutive time.  By establishing new partnerships within the public and private sectors, expanding the use of technology, and administering an award-winning advertising campaign, the Illinois Bureau of Tourism expects to continue this outstanding growth.<p>

Tourism's success reflects positively on the overall Illinois economy.  During Calendar Year 1995 (the most recent data available), domestic and international travel within Illinois showed a direct economic impact of $16 billion -- a 3.2 percent improvement over the $15.5 billion spent in 1994.  This includes an 8.75 percent increase in international travel to Illinois, which is now the sixth most popular U.S. state for overseas visitors.<p>

Besides the direct economic impact, tourism generates jobs; in fact approximately one in 10 Illinois workers is directly or indirectly dependent on tourism for employment.  In 1995, the Illinois travel industry employed 335,500 workers and contributed to the need for another 354,700 indirect jobs.  The travel-generated payroll in Illinois was $5.8 billion, an increase of 3.8 percent over 1994.<p>  

Travel is also good for the state treasury.  Travelers in Illinois contributed $3.7 billion in taxes during 1995.  State hotel/motel taxes, a portion of which fund all Illinois tourism programs, were up 10 percent during that time, reaching $111.7 million.<p>

The Illinois Bureau of Tourism is working with its Illinois travel partners to continue this record of success.  In addition to the successful "Million Miles from Monday" campaign, the Bureau administers a sophisticated travel counseling system that enables customers to customize travel plans with a simple phone call (1-800-2-CONNECT, TTY users call 800/406-6418); a web site (www.enjoyillinois.com) that gives users trip ideas, trip planning opportunities and updates on festivals and events; and an ambitious international marketing initiative that targets travelers in Canada, the United Kingdom and Germany.  The Bureau also administers the Tourism Matching Grant program, the Tourism Private Sector grant program, and the Illinois Convention and Visitors Bureau grant program, which provide assistance to local units of government and local organizations to help promote and market travel-related activities in their areas.<p>

New technologies being implemented by the Illinois Bureau of Tourism enable the Bureau to identify Illinois' best tourism customers, thus making it easier to target efforts toward motivating them to travel in Illinois.  These technologies, combined with the Bureau's other activities, should help to keep Illinois at the forefront in travel industry growth.<p>

<h4 align=center>###</h4>

<hr>
<h3>ENERGYWISE HOMES OF ILLINOIS GETS TOP BILLING IN SUN-TIMES ARTICLE</h3>

DCCA's EnergyWise Homes of Illinois program recently received front-page status in the Chicago Sun-Times weekend HOMELIFE section.  The story, which pointed out ways the program can help homeowners save substantial dollars while promoting energy conservation, has been a real boost to efforts to educate the general public about the benefits of home energy conservation.<p>

The story, written by Hilary Anderson, focused on energy-efficient mortgages that use standardized ratings to determine the energy efficiency of both newly-constructed homes and existing dwellings.  By qualifying for an Energy Edge Mortgage (EEM), those who purchase energy-efficient homes often can extend their debt ratios, thus enabling them to purchase a higher-priced home because of its lower monthly energy costs.  Energy Improvement Mortgages (EIMs) that finance improvements that make existing homes more energy efficient also are available to many current homeowners and those seeking to purchase such homes.<p>

To qualify for the special mortgages, homes must undergo an energy audit, conducted by a certified home energy rater.  These raters collect data on the home's energy efficiency and enter the data into a computer at DCCA's Bureau of Energy and Recycling.  DCCA then issues a home energy rating and a report that recommends areas where energy improvements could be made.<p>  

The ratings may be used by homeowners or builders to assist in qualifying for the special loans, but they also can be used as important informational tools in helping homeowners identify ways to increase a home's energy efficiency.<p>

For more information about the EnergyWise Homes of Illinois program, contact John Marley at DCCA's Bureau of Energy and Recycling at 217/785-2007 (TDD users call 217/785-0211).<p>

<h4 align=center>###</h4>

<hr>
<h3>IMA ANNOUNCES TEAM EXCELLENCE AWARD COMPETITION</h3>

Move over Bulls, Blackhawks and Bears -- a whole new kind of team spirit is sweeping Illinois, and it's saving Illinois companies thousands of dollars every year.  Employees of Illinois companies are teaming together to develop innovative ways to improve quality, reduce costs and build enthusiasm on the job.  These impressive efforts are deserving of recognition, and they're getting it through the Illinois Team Excellence Award.<p>

The Illinois Team Excellence Award was founded by the Illinois Manufacturers' Association to provide a forum for Illinois employees to show how their involvement, teamwork and innovation make Illinois businesses more competitive and successful.  In the past four years, nearly 100 companies have illustrated their team projects in 15-minute presentations to audiences of peers, program judges and the public in the competition for this Illinois team-based quality award.<p>

Everybody wins in the Illinois Team Excellence Award program.  Team players whose ideas have worked to better the company take to the stage with their projects and shine in the spotlight.  Companies supporting teamwork demonstrate and publicize their commitment to employee empowerment.  The program is an active exchange among the state's most innovative companies and employees, sharing ideas for a strong and healthy business climate in Illinois.<p>

Since excellence knows no boundaries, the program welcomes all Illinois businesses, be they manufacturing, service, government agencies, educational institutions and health care providers.<p>

This year, the Illinois Team Excellence Award program culminated in the IMA's Quest for Excellence, a day of teaching, training, learning and celebrating people and quality held in October in Rosemont.  Nine teams that had advanced from the regional stage of the competition polished their team presentations for one more performance to a record-breaking crowd.  While teams presented their projects throughout the day, breakout sessions featured expert speakers on issues such as management practices in the 21st Century, organizational survival in the next century, recognizing and rewarding employees and continuous quality improvement.<p>

In the end, Motorola, Quartz Products Division, of Schaumburg claimed the large company title, and Craftsman Custom Metal Fabricators, Inc. of Schiller Park netted the top small company prize.  The silver medal in the large company division went to Caterpillar Inc.'s Aurora plant, and bronze to Brach and Brock Confections of Chicago.  Rockford's Zenith Cutter Co. claimed the silver in the small company division, and Alpharma of Chicago Heights took home the bronze.<p>

Companies of all shapes and sizes with a plant or headquarters in Illinois are invited to participate in the 1997 Illinois Team Excellence Award program.  Entry forms will be available in February.  A video of the 1996 Illinois Team Excellence Awards also is available from the Illinois Manufacturers' Association at a cost of $9.00.  <p>

For an application or more information about the Illinois Team Excellence Award program, contact Jane Frech, vice president of Public Affairs, at the Illinois Manufacturers' Association, 220 E. Adams St., Springfield, IL  62701-1123.<p>

<h4 align=center>###</h4>

<hr>
<h3>EXPORTS KEY TO THE FUTURE OF ILLINOIS COAL</h3>

Developing new export markets for Illinois coal is key to the future of the coal mining industry in our state, according to a new report, Export Markets for Illinois Coal, prepared for DCCA's Office of Coal Development and Marketing (OCDM).<p>

The report notes that global demand for coal will rise dramatically over the next decade as more countries turn to coal for electricity generation.  In particular, the Atlantic market is expected to grow by 20 to 30 million tons.<p>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, Gov. Jim Edgar's senior adviser for economic development, said, "Our goal should be to identify where Illinois coal can be competitive and target those markets.  There are some 'niche' markets we should be able to penetrate -- markets where Illinois producers can deliver the coal efficiently and where the quality of our coal matches the demand of the buyers."<p>

Aggressive industry marketing resulted in a ten-fold increase in Illinois coal exports in 1995, reaching a record 2.7 million tons, with Morocco, Germany, the United Kingdom and Denmark as major buyers.  Kustra noted that a new $2 million initiative, recently announced by Gov. Edgar, will be instrumental in OCDM's efforts to further market Illinois coal to prospective buyers.  The funds will be used to develop information and contacts that Illinois coal producers can use to target specific foreign markets.  <p>

"The Illinois coal industry continues to face many challenges," Kustra said.  "We are committed to working closely with the industry to help promote Illinois coal exports.  Exports represent not only a realistic marketing objective, but a potential stabilizing force in these challenging times."<p>

To receive a copy of Export Markets for Illinois Coal, contact Dan Keefe at DCCA, telephone 217/782-6135 (TDD users call 217/785-0211).<p>

<h4 align=center>###</h4>

<hr>
<h3>FEDERAL GRANT HELPS EXPAND TECHNICAL SERVICES FOR SMALL AND MID-SIZED ILLINOIS MANUFACTURERS</h3>

Small and medium-sized manufacturers in Illinois just got a better tool to help their efforts to utilize new technologies to modernize and expand for the future.<p>

The National Institute for Standards and Technology (NIST) recently awarded a $2.67 million grant that, coupled with $1.2 million in state grants and in-kind contributions from private resources, will help the Illinois Manufacturing Extension Center (IMEC) expand and improve its services. IMEC, located at Bradley University in Peoria with sub-centers on the campuses of Rock Valley College in Rockford and Southern Illinois University at Carbondale, is part of DCCA's statewide Manufacturing Extension Partnership of Illinois.  IMEC field offices are located in the Quad Cities, Joliet, LaSalle-Peru, Bloomington-Normal, Springfield and Edwardsville.  DCCA was a partner both in the creation of IMEC and in the preparation of the successful grant application.  <p>

IMEC provides a range of technical services to firms, including manufacturing assessment, engineering assistance, modernization demonstrations, support in product and network development, and referrals for services provided by other private firms.<p>

The federal grant will help IMEC expand its offerings at existing offices and add four new field extension offices.  The goal is to ensure that 80 percent of the state's small and medium-sized manufacturers can access an office within 40 miles of their locations.<p>

"We're delighted that federal officials agree with us that Illinois small and medium-sized manufacturers need and deserve public support as they strive to take full advantage of global market opportunities and grow stronger," said Gov. Jim Edgar.  The Governor pointed out that the grant, coupled with his administration's financial support over the past several years, will mean that the state's small and medium-sized businesses can enjoy an even more comprehensive level of technical support and assistance as they seek to enhance productivity, improve technology and compete more effectively.<p>

IMEC and the Manufacturing Extension Partnership of Illinois replace the pilot "Project COMPETE" technology extension effort.<p>

For more information about IMEC or the Manufacturing Extension Partnership of Illinois, contact Jack MacLennan in DCCA's Office of Business Technology and Competitiveness at 312/814-2366 (TDD users call 800/419-0667).<p>

<h4 align=center>###</h4>

<hr>
