<CENTER><H2>August, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<HR>


<h3>NEW REPORT ANALYZES UTILITY RESTRUCTURING; EFFECT ON COAL</h3>

<em>by Dan Keefe, DCCA Division of Coal Development and Marketing</em><p>

As the electric utility industry moves away from regulated service and closer to a competitive marketplace, the Illinois coal industry faces an uncertain future, according to a new report from DCCA's Office of Coal Development and Marketing (OCDM).  The report, "Illinois Coal Industry White Paper:  Understanding Electric Utility Restructuring," prepared by the Center for Regulatory Studies at Illinois State University, has been well-received by both coal and utility industry professionals as a thorough analysis of restructuring issues and their potential impact on coal markets.<p>

Just as telecommunications, airlines, trucking, banking and natural gas industries have undergone deregulation, the electric utility industry is now being targeted by free-market policymakers whose primary objective is to bring down the cost of electric services by allowing market forces, rather than government regulators, to set the price of these services.  Federal and state governments are working to accomplish the goal by considering various scenarios for replacing regulation with competition.<p>

The OCDM White Paper discusses several possible outcomes of the various restructuring efforts.  First, there likely will be consolidation of electric utilities as they seek more efficient operating structures (for example, the proposed merger between Central Illinois Public Service Company and Union Electric.)  Second, most jurisdictions will move from the traditional rate-of-return regulation (cost plus profit), to a performance-based regulatory system where costs are separated from revenues, thus giving utilities incentive to reduce costs.  Third, many expect development of regional power pools, where spot market transactions, administered by an Independent System Operator (ISO) are prevalent.  Fourth, due to separation of electric utility generation, transmission and distribution functions, consumers will have greater choice in both the type of service they receive and from whom they receive it.  Finally, the generation sector of the electricity market is likely to become competitive first, since federal policy decisions over the last 20 years have largely negated the monopoly characteristics of power production, wholesale power transactions and resource additions.<p>

It is difficult to predict what these changes will bring to the Illinois coal industry; however, in the near term, some observers predict that with an emphasis on efficiency, existing coal-fired power plants will increase production because of their lower marginal generation costs.  This would trigger an increase in coal sales.  Still, over the long-term, it is likely that older, less efficient coal-fired generating plants could be retired or converted to natural gas.<p>

Thus, the newest challenge facing Illinois coal is to retain as much existing market share as possible, while seeking out new markets for this efficient fuel.  Nearly all electric utility restructuring analyses project a near-term gain, mid-term loss, and long-term benefit for coal as the cost-effective fuel of choice for baseload electricity generation.  OCDM will continue to work with the Illinois coal industry to ensure that this valuable commodity plays a prominent role in a restructured electric utility marketplace.<p>

For more information about the OCDM White Paper, contact Dan Keefe in DCCA's Office of Coal Development and Marketing, at 217/782-6135 (TDD:  217/785-0211).<p>


<hr>
<h3>MEXICAN COMPANY OPENS SHUTTERED SPARTA PLANT</h3>

Gov. Jim Edgar awarded a $500,000 Community Development Assistance Program (CDAP) grant to Sparta Mayor Greg Aitken, as representatives Pedro Booth and Sergio Guarneros of Grupo Serla S.A. de C.V. looked on.  The grant is part of an $860,000 package of state assistance to assist Grupo Serla in renovating the former Spartan Printing plant.  The plant, which had been shuttered since February, is expected to employ at least 300 workers when it opens early next year.  Grupo Serla, Mexico's leading producer of Spanish-language textbooks, intends to target the U.S. market and also will pursue contracts with customers of the former Spartan plant. <p>


<hr>
<h3>CONFERENCE HELPS SMALL AND MID-SIZED COMPANIES <br>
BECOME SUCCESSFUL EXPORTERS</h3>
<em>by Mary Anne Brown-Rogerio, DCCA International Business Division</em><p>

More than 650 business people learned valuable information to help them become successful exporters during the second annual Crossing International Borders conference, recently held in Chicago.  The conference, cosponsored by DCCA and Arthur Andersen, in collaboration with 22 international associations and agencies, provided exporters with the best and latest information on becoming effective exporters.  It also featured presentations by the managing directors of Illinois' foreign offices, who provided market updates on the Far East, North Asia, the Americas, Western Europe and Eastern Europe, as well as presentations by professionals from Arthur Andersen and other companies.<p>

Participants in the conference were greeted by DCCA Director Dennis Whetstone, who spoke on the challenges and rewards of doing business overseas.  Luncheon featured remarks from Casey Cowell, co-founder of U.S. Robotics, a leader in the manufacture of information access products, who discussed his company's international strategy.  Participants had their choice of 36 concurrent workshops which covered the current status of trade agreements, export financing, legal concerns, customs issues, the human resource factor, reducing taxes, finding overseas distributors, protecting intellectual property, foreign sales corporations and international franchising.  The conference concluded with an International Export Forum, which featured the opportunity for one-on-one consultation with the experts.<p>

A highlight of the conference was the presentation of the Governor's Export Awards.  Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra presented the awards to 15 Illinois companies and associations, representing four categories.  Winners of the "New to Export" award included Westell International, Sabratek Corporation, Total Process Corp. and Visiontek.  "Continuing Export Excellence" awards went to Prince Castle, Inc.; The Chicago Stock Exchange, Inc.; Fluid Management L.P.; Frasca International, Inc.; and DICKEY-john.  Awards for "Export Awareness and Development" were presented to the Automotive Exporters' Council, the National Housewares Manufacturers Association; Central Illinois Exporters' Association and the Illinois Wheat Association.  Winners of the "Community Service Recognition Award" were the U.S.-Mexico Chamber of Commerce and JETRO Chicago.<p>

Illinois is the fifth-largest exporting state in the nation, with nearly 500,000 jobs linked to exporting.  The "Crossing International Borders" conference can help even more Illinois businesses become better exporters.<p>


<hr>
<h3>ILLINOIS OPENS PUBLIC E-85 REFUELING FACILITIES </h3>

DCCA's Office of Energy Conservation and Alternative Energy works closely with Illinois agricultural organizations and automobile manufacturers to promote and expand the use of ethanol as a clean-burning, renewable transportation fuel.  The recent opening of the three public E-85 refueling stations will play an important role in that effort.<p>

In June, Mitch Beaver, Deputy Director of DCCA's Bureau of Energy and Recycling,   participated in grand opening ceremonies at the E-85 station in Dwight at Exit 220 on Interstate 55.  With remarks from U.S. Congressman Tom Ewing, state Sen. John Maitland, Chet Boruff of the Illinois Department of Agriculture, Mike Lockhart of Growmark, Inc., Vic Riddle of the Illinois Corn Growers, and Beaver, the ceremonies highlighted the partnership that has helped to encourage expansion of ethanol usage.<p>

Ethanol is important to Illinois.  Our state leads the nation in the production of ethanol, and ranks first or second in the production of corn each year.  DCCA's Bureau of Energy and Recycling assists this industry by managing numerous ethanol test and demonstration projects, and sponsoring the research and development of new and innovative technologies to help reduce ethanol production costs.  Among its projects are partnerships with General Motors and Ford Motor Company to field-test flexible-fuel vehicles designed to operate on either traditional gasoline or E-85 fuel -- a mixture of 85 percent denatured ethanol with 15 percent natural gasoline added to aid in fuel combustion.<p>

The new Dwight station, owned and operated by Livingston County FS and supplied by Growmark, is one of three E-85 stations now open to the public in Illinois.  Others include a SuperAmerica E-85 station in Des Plaines and a Mobil station in Springfield.  Plans call for up to 40 E-85 stations in Chicago, Rockford, Peoria, the Quad Cities and other communities in Illinois and throughout the Midwest.<p>


<hr>
<h3>IEZA CONFERENCE OFFERS VALUABLE TRAINING</h3>
       
DCCA Director Dennis Whetstone joined Jeanne Gustafson, President of the Illinois Enterprise Zone Association (IEZA), and Tom Henderson, DCCA's Enterprise Zone program manager, at the Illinois Enterprise Zone Administrators' Training Session, held in June in Springfield.   More than 150 communities were represented at the conference, which featured sessions on incentives, zone marketing, reporting requirements, zone alterations and use of the Internet.<p>


<hr>
<h3>DCCA IMPLEMENTING "TOTAL QUALITY MANAGEMENT"</h3>

Total Quality Management, or TQM, is a philosophy being embraced in many industries today.  TQM involves the entire workforce, tapping the knowledge and expertise of individual workers at all levels of responsibility to help find better, faster and more efficient ways of doing a job, whether it be manufacturing widgets or providing a service.<p>

Over the past year, DCCA has been incorporating the TQM philosophy into its programs and services.  Since June 1995, 120 DCCA employees have completed TQM training to help them understand the philosophy and procedures involved in the TQM process.  This training has helped 15 TQM "teams" begin work on studying various DCCA processes and procedures, researching and developing recommendations to streamline these activities while improving quality of the services provided to both internal and external customers.  For example, teams have studied the contracting process, grant processing, payroll procedures, policy letters and other processes and procedures undertaken daily within the department.  Ten teams have already submitted their recommendations for change to Director Dennis Whetstone and top management for their approval, and steps toward implementation of their recommendations have begun.<p>

TQM is expected to have many benefits for DCCA.  The philosophy brings DCCA's employees directly into the front line to help identify barriers to quality service and uses their expertise to develop ways to break down those barriers.  In addition, by improving the quality of its processes, DCCA will be able to serve its customers in a more timely and less cumbersome manner.  Finally, TQM gives DCCA's employees a sense that they are important members of a team working together to make the agency a better place.<p>


<hr>
<h3>FORUM ADDRESSES RURAL POVERTY</h3>

<em>by Curt Farrar, DCCA Division of Economic Opportunity</em><p>

Poverty is a problem that knows no geographic boundaries.  According to the 1990 census, poverty is particularly growing in non-metropolitan areas of Illinois.  As populations age and economic opportunities decline, rural communities need assistance to reverse the problem.  Phyllis "Phib" Bell of DCCA's Division of Economic Opportunity is one of those actively working to help.  Saying, "We often forget that poverty also occurs in rural areas," Bell recently helped organize the "Pathways From Poverty Forum," held in Collinsville.<p>

The forum, co-sponsored by the W. K. Kellogg Foundation, the Farm Foundation, and the Rural Sociological Society Task Force on Rural Poverty, attracted more than 120 leaders from state and local organizations in 12 Midwestern states.  Some states sent as many as 15 people to participate in the conference, which was designed to increase understanding and awareness of both the individual and social aspects of poverty and stimulate thinking about steps that can be taken to create "pathways" from poverty.  Another primary objective was to build stronger relationships and facilitate communication among organizations involved in rural poverty.<p>

Forum participants developed a vision statement and action plan to stimulate more job opportunities, involve the disadvantaged in the political process, and increase access to more meaningful educational opportunities in rural areas.  The W. K. Kellogg Foundation has already committed seed funds of $1,500 to support a statewide rural poverty conference in November 1996 to continue advancing rural poverty initiatives.<p>

Members of the Illinois team participating in the forum included Ted Aggen, Mayor of Sterling; Doug Dougherty, Executive Director of the Rural Affairs Council, Lt. Gov. Kustra's office; Betty Green, Director, RIDES Mass Transit District, Rosiclare; Jack Halstead, Senior Editor, Association of Illinois Electric Cooperatives, Springfield; Sue Mahoney, retired teacher, Rosiclare; Jane Pfeiffer, Mayor of Elsah; Jane Poertner, Director, Central Illinois Economic Development Corporation, Lincoln; Ann Heinz-Silvis, Extension Specialist, University of Illinois Laboratory for Community and Economic Development, Urbana; and Randy Sumner, Vice President of Community Affairs, Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis.   <p>


<hr>
<h3>GETTING THE WORD OUT ABOUT SMALL BUSINESS PROGRAMS</h3>

Although large corporations grab the headlines, small businesses are the driving force behind America's economy.  Obtaining financing for business start-up or expansion, however, can be one of the largest hurdles for entrepreneurs.  DCCA's Small Business Division within the Bureau of Business Development is working to make sure that Illinois small business people know about the many programs available to help them achieve success.<p>

In April, the Division underwrote the costs associated with airing the public television series, "Small Business 2000," on the Convocom network (WMEC-Macomb, WQEC-Quincy and WSEC-Springfield/Jacksonville).  Each of the half-hour programs included news stories and regular features on marketing, law and technology, as well as special presentations on home offices, professional practices, book reviews and reviews of the latest in computer software.  <p>

Throughout May and June, the Division hosted a series of Lenders' Forums at locations throughout the state.  The forums featured officials from several government lending agencies, including DCCA, the Illinois Development Finance Authority (IDFA), the U.S. Export Assistance Center (USEAC) and the U.S. Small Business Administration (SBA).  The forums gave bankers and other commercial lenders insight into DCCA's Participation Loan Program, the USEAC's Export Working Capital Loan Program, SBA's Low-Doc program, and IDFA's Direct Loan, Microloan and Industrial Revenue Bonds.  Participants got a look at upcoming changes and forecasts about the financing programs, as well as an opportunity for one-on-one discussions.<p>

Over the past decade, DCCA's Small Business Division has provided more than $500 million in business financing, helping small businesses retain more than 35,000 Illinos jobs and retain nearly 48,000 jobs.<p>


<hr>
