<CENTER><H2>May, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<HR>

<h3>Small Businesses Drive the Illinois Economy</h3>

<h4>By Roberta Janis and Joe Weiss, DCCA Small Business Division</h4>

Small business is the real muscle of the Illinois economy.  Recent data shows that 85  percent of the new jobs in Illinois were created by small businesses, and nearly 4.4 million Illinois workers depend on small business for their livelihood.<p> 

To achieve business success, today's small business owners have to wear many hats -- that of a banker to secure financing, a marketing expert to reach potential clientele, an accountant to file a myriad of tax returns, and the list goes on.<p>

Fortunately for Illinois' 617,000 small business owners, assistance is readily available. Whether shopping for a marketplace, investigating financial sources or trying to make sense of tax requirements, DCCA's Small Business Division can help.  <p>

The Small Business Division includes 40 Small Business Development Centers (SBDCs), 13 Procurement Technical Assistance Centers, five International Trade Centers, two NAFTA Opportunity Centers, 20 Incubators, an Office of Minority Business Development, an Office of Women's Business Development, an Office of Small Business Environmental Assistance and the First-Stop Business Information Center.<p>

SBDCs counsel, conduct research, and train business people in a wide variety of business topics.  They provide comprehensive information services and access to experts in many fields.  Centers develop and maintain partnerships among community organizations and local, state and federal agencies, providing a focal point for broad networks of public and private resources at the community level.  These partnership programs and activities serve small business and contribute significantly to the economic growth in Illinois.<p>

An example is the new Super 8 Motel in Greenville, Illinois.  Although they had been involved in other successful business ventures, 32-year-old Vicki Ellsworth and her associates turned to the SBDC at Kaskaskia College in Centralia for help in opening the new motel.  The SBDC not only helped develop a business plan and compiled three- and five-year projections, but also helped compile a financial package that included an $800,000 loan guaranteed by the U.S. Small Business Administration (SBA) and $150,000 from the Illinois Development Finance Authority (IDFA).  After only a few months of operation, the Greenville Super 8 has already exceeded its projections.<p>

Vern Carlsen is another example.  Carlsen worked for 25 years at a Chicago area industrial company, working his way up to corporate vice president.  After the company was sold in 1988, he worked as a salesman for a few years, then became a manager and contract administrator for a Rockford firm.  In that job, he discovered that, although many companies were interested in doing business with the government, they did not want to deal with the paperwork involved.  Carlsen started Sales Assistance Service in 1993 to fill this void.  Sales Assistance Service used the services of the Procurement Technical Assistance Center at Rock Valley College in Rockford, particularly the automated bid service and the specification library.  The company also has begun to use Electronic Data Interchange to receive bids daily.  It is now a successful business that continues to expand. <p> 

Over the past decade, DCCA's Small Business Division has compiled impressive statistics.  To find out if the Small Business Division can help you, call 800/252-2923 (TDD:  800/785-6055.)<p>

<h4>Big Help for Small Businesses</h4>

Over the past decade, DCCA's Small Business Division has compiled an impressive record of success:<p>
<ul type=square>
<li>251,326 Counseled
<li>$485,036,718 in Business Financing
<li>$1,270,056,503 in Government Contracts
<li>$47,414,250 in Export Sales
<li>35,446 Jobs Created
<li>47,966 Jobs Retained
<li>25,998 Minorities Counseled
<li>36,890 Women Counseled
<li>1,225 Assisted by First Stop Business Information Center (since August 1995)
<li>2,092 Receiving Environmental Regulatory Assistance (since November 1994)
</ul>

<hr>
<h3>From the Director</h3>

<h4>What is Economic Development?</h4>

DCCA's new mission statement says that DCCA is the "lead state agency responsible for improving the competitiveness of Illinois in the global economy resulting in prosperous, growing industries, rising real incomes and high quality jobs."<p>

But the agency's programs and services encompass a wide range of activities -- tourism, help for local governments, workforce training programs, assistance to low-income people, technology assistance, site and building location assistance, small business assistance, and many more.  How do all these programs fit the definition of economic development?<p>

Think like a mayor.  As mayor, you are vitally interested in the future of your community.  You want it to be a great place for families to live and visit, with prosperous businesses, plentiful jobs, convenient services and a healthy environment.  <p>

You're interested in infrastructure because you know that without access to safe and adequate water supplies and waste treatment, safe roads and other foundations, people and businesses will not want to live in and locate in your community.  You're interested in workforce development because you want to ensure that businesses in your community have the skilled workers they need to stay competitive in a global marketplace.  You also know that the future of your current businesses, as well as your ability to attract more businesses and jobs, depends on a continued supply of skilled workers and adequate infrastructure.<p>

You're interested in maintaining and improving the quality of life for residents in your community.  You want to ensure that low-income families have decent, energy efficient homes in which to live and the ability to pay their winter energy bills.  You want to provide services to homeless people to help them get back on their feet.  And you want to help low-income and disadvantaged people find employment opportunities and learn the skills they need to be productive employees.<p>

You know that if your community is to grow, you need to encourage existing businesses to expand and attract new businesses and jobs.  That's not just large factories -- it's also encouraging entrepreneurs to start new businesses, like the corner cafe, the dry cleaning shop and others that provide the services your citizens need.  <p>

You have a nice community.  You want others to enjoy it.  You're interested in promoting your community and its resources to tourists who will spend their dollars in your hotels and motels, restaurants and shops while enjoying the sights.<p>

If all of these things are beginning to sound familiar, it's because they are all addressed by the programs DCCA administers.  The Bureau of Community Development, for example, helps smaller Illinois communities address their infrastructure and housing needs through the Community Development Assistance Program (CDAP).  Job Training Partnership Act (JTPA) programs and the Industrial Training Program (ITP) help train people in the skills they need to be productive employees.  Community Service Block Grant (CSBG) programs provide loans to help start businesses that provide jobs to disadvantaged workers, as well as many services to help low-income people break out of poverty.  The Low Income Home Energy Assistance Program (LIHEAP) helps low-income families pay a portion of their winter energy bills, while the Illinois Home Weatherization Assistance Program (IHWAP) helps low-income families make their dwellings more energy-efficient.<p>  

DCCA's Business Development Bureau provides site selection and technical assistance to help attract new businesses to Illinois, as well as services to help existing businesses grow, such as export assistance.  Through the First-Stop Business Information Center and the Illinois Small Business Development Center Network, DCCA helps entrepreneurs and small business owners find answers to their questions, locate business capital, start new businesses and expand existing ones.  <p>

The Bureau of Tourism promotes Illinois and provides assistance to help local communities and regions market themselves in this fast-growing industry, and also promotes Illinois as a site for film and television production.  Coal Development and Marketing programs work to find and market new, environmentally-safe methods of using Illinois' greatest resource.  The Bureau of Energy and Recycling promotes sustainable economic development by encouraging alternative energy resource development such as ethanol; improving energy efficiency in residences, buildings and factories which also helps reduce costs; and by supporting recycling and waste reduction programs, including the expansion of markets for recycled materials.  These programs facilitate the efficient use of natural resources while helping to minimize negative impacts on the environment. <p>
 
What is economic development?  A mayor knows.  He or she knows that a community that looks to the future and addresses its needs will be a competitive community that attracts and keeps prosperous, growing industries.  Those industries will provide high quality jobs that pay the kind of rising real incomes that can fund the parks, schools, infrastructure and other public services that make others want to visit and make the community their home.  With the right help, a mayor can close the circle into a continuous cycle of development.<p>

DCCA was created in 1979 to be Illinois' lead economic development agency.  The various community, workforce and business development programs were merged under the DCCA umbrella for a reason -- because they all are essential components of our state's ability to improve its competitiveness in a global economy.  Today, more than ever, DCCA must recognize its unique ability to be the state's "one-stop" economic development agency.  Understanding that role, and the ways our various programs fit into the overall mission, is the first step toward fulfilling that mission.<p>


<hr>
<h3>Illinois Ventures for Community Action Provides Crucial Resources</h3>

<h4>by Curt Farrar, DCCA Division of Economic Opportunity</h4>

More than $3.6 million in loans, 616 new jobs and the lowest loan default rate in the nation.  That's a great record, and one the people at Illinois Ventures for Community Action (IVCA) are proud of.<p>

IVCA is a private 501c(3) not-for-profit corporation located in Springfield that works with the 34 local Community Action Agencies (CAAs) in Illinois and other public and private enterprises to facilitate economic development within the state.  In particular, IVCA helps ensure that CAAs have the training and knowledge they need to develop loans to businesses that can create jobs for low-income Illinoisans -- a key component of the federally-funded Community Services Block Grant (CSBG) program, administered in Illinois by DCCA.<p>

Formed in 1985, IVCA is administered by a Board composed of representatives from 16 CAAs.  It is directed by CEO Michael Chew, a financial professional and former bank president.  Working closely with DCCA's Division of Economic Opportunities and the CAAs, IVCA helps the CAAs market their loans and loan services, provides lending consultation training and technical assistance with the lending function, and helps maintain coordination with lead lenders in the communities.  Through these services, IVCA is helping CAAs improve the quality of their loan portfolios.  IVCA also explores new sources of capital and tools for economic development activities, such as equity and ownership positions in Illinois businesses, to generate sustainable revenue streams that can be used to support anti-poverty efforts.<p>

For example, IVCA has assisted five CAAs in purchasing their own office buildings, thus enabling them to build a capital asset for the agency while improving creditability in the community through real estate ownership.  Chew considers the building acquisition program for Community Action Agencies to be one of the most important services IVCA performs, saying "The fiscal benefit of real estate ownership equates to immeasurable benefit to the community."<p>

Since its inception, IVCA has closed more than $3.6 million in loans, created 616 jobs, and has the distinctive record of never having a job default loan in its portfolio.  Its loan default ratio is 3.49 percent.  Since 1989, the loan default ratio has been less than one percent.  In fact, according to the Federal Office of Community Services, IVCA has the lowest loan default rate of any loan program it monitors.<p>

DCCA's partnership with Illinois Ventures for Community Action is one way DCCA is working to find innovative ways to strengthen local efforts and provide communities access to resources for physical and social infrastructure improvements.<p>  


<hr>
<h3>
Workshops Help Illinois Businesses<br>
Explore Export Opportunities
</h3>

Illinois businesses that want to explore the export marketplace or need information about expanding their exporting potential can obtain valuable assistance at a series of regional workshops scheduled over the coming months in Illinois.<p>

The DCCA-sponsored workshops are geared toward export opportunities in six of the 10 Big Emerging Markets (BEMs) -- markets identified as being particularly receptive to goods and services offered by U.S. companies.  The six markets deemed particularly receptive to Illinois-made products and services include South Africa, Korea and the Pacific Rim, China, Poland and Eastern Europe, Mexico and Latin America, and Turkey.   The workshops are made possible through a Market Development Cooperator Program grant awarded to Illinois by the U.S. Department of Commerce -- one of only eight such grants awarded this year.<p>

Illinois' network of International Trade Centers (ITCs) and NAFTA Opportunity Centers, two components of the Illinois Small Business Development Center Network (ISBDCN), will coordinate the workshops.  Each workshop will offer participants a chance to learn about the specific export opportunities in each market and experiences of companies already exporting to that country.  In addition, representatives from DCCA's International Business Division will discuss export assistance services offered in various Illinois pavilions scheduled for BEM trade shows, as well as assistance offered in locating potential agents and distributors.<p>

Upcoming workshops include a May 29 seminar at Bradley University in Peoria to discuss strategies for success in Korea and the Pacific Rim, and a May 30 seminar at the College of Du Page in Glen Ellyn focusing on International Quality Standards as they relate to markets in Poland, Korea and China.  Other future workshops will be held at Bradley and College of DuPage, as well as at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, Southern Illinois University at Edwardsville, and  NORBIC in Chicago.<p>

For further information about the workshops, contact Roberta Janis at DCCA at 312/814-7170 (TDD:  312/419-0667).<p>

<hr>
<h3>DCCA Establishes Business & Industry Data Center Program</h3>

Small business people will be able to conveniently access census data and other usable information through a new service being established at DCCA.  The Business and Industry Data Center Program (BIDC), designed to enhance the BIDC program started by the U.S. Bureau of the Census in 1988, will give small business people, independent contractors and future businesses in Illinois an easy way to obtain statistical data and other sources of practical information. <p>

Statistics can be very important to small business people in planning, marketing, managing and expanding their businesses.  The BIDC program will utilize a system of five regional affiliates in Illinois to collect and provide basic information to the small business community, complete complex analyses as needed and perform regional economic analyses.  A system of three to five local affiliates in each region will deal directly with small businesses and other data users, providing basic census, economic and demographic information; data prepared by the regional affiliates or the state; and technical assistance with basic data interpretation.  The BIDC program also is affiliated with DCCA's First-Stop Business Information Center, which offers services and products designed to help new and existing businesses determine regulations applicable to their business activity and general start-up information. <p>

A few examples of BIDC assistance include information on commonly-offered  employee benefits in selected industries; listings of office furniture manufacturers; county economic profiles; trade show listings; numbers of Illinois businesses in select SIC codes that have sales of more than $1 million; city population, income and growth projections; ACT scores by school district; and numbers and sizes of warehouses in a county.<p>

For more information about the BIDC program, contact one of the BIDCs or phone Ed Taft at DCCA, 217/785-7545 (TDD:  800/785-6055).<p>

