<CENTER><H2>March, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<HR>

<h3>ITP GRANT HELPS KEEP QUALITY AS "JOB ONE"</h3>

Nearly 3,000 workers at Ford Motor Company's Chicago Assembly plant and its Illinois supplier firms will learn new skills to help them be more productive employees, thanks to an $800,000 Industrial Training Program grant announced by Gov. Jim Edgar during a January visit to the plant.<p>

The grant, the latest in a series of ITP awards to Ford since Fiscal Year 1989,  highlights the important relationship between DCCA and Illinois companies in providing the training needed to keep Illinois worker skills among the best in the world.   ITP grants are an investment in Illinois workers that can help tip the scales in favor of Illinois when companies make location, expansion or modernization decisions.<p>

Ford, for example, has been manufacturing automobiles in Chicago since 1914, and started production at the Torrence Avenue facility in 1924.  Over the years, the plant has been expanded and modernized, currently producing the Ford Taurus and Mercury Sable automobiles.  The Chicago Assembly plant supplies vehicles throughout the U.S. and exports vehicles to 17 countries.<p>

A commitment to quality has always been foremost.  In July 1995, Ford awarded the Chicago Assembly Plant its Ford Q1 (Quality 1) designation.  That commitment, coupled with exacting export requirements demanded by established international quality standards, makes it necessary for Ford to continuously provide training programs to upgrade the skills and knowledge of its workers.<p>

Using its latest ITP grant, Ford will work with equipment suppliers, Ford personnel, and local schools and universities to develop and conduct training activities.  Included in the training is problem solving, continuous improvement methods, statistical process control, communications techniques and leadership skills.  Preventive maintenance systems, quality operating systems, computer skills, technical equipment courses and online production operations training are also part of the total training plan.  A heavy emphasis will be placed on process improvement and international quality measurements, such as ISO 9002.<p>

In its quest to ensure that "Quality is Job One," Ford also is inviting many of its Illinois supplier companies to participate in the training program.  Those companies include the Ford Chicago Stamping Plant in Chicago Heights; Certified Tool of Elk Grove Village; ELCO Industries, Inc. of Rockford, ITW Deltar Insert Molded Products in Elk Grove Village; Littlefuse, Inc. in Des Plaines; and MacLean-Fogg Company of Mundelein.<p>

This supplier training is a relatively new aspect of ITP.  In its early years, the program was restricted to Illinois manufacturers to assist with training and retraining costs.  In 1992, the program was expanded to include multi-company and intermediary organizations -- community colleges, original equipment manufacturers like Ford providing training to workers from their Illinois supplier network, business and industry associations, labor organizations, and strategic business partnerships -- among those eligible for grant funding.  This new emphasis enables today's ITP to reach out to a broader segment of the Illinois business community, particularly small and medium-sized companies with similar training needs.<p>

Since its inception in Fiscal Year 1979, the Industrial Training Program has provided nearly $168.7 million to help train more than 287,000 Illinois workers.  Entirely funded through state General Revenue Funds, the grants reimburse companies or organizations up to 50 percent of the cost of training efforts.  By providing grants to multi-company and intermediary organizations, ITP funds are training more workers than ever before while lowering per-worker training costs.<p>

In speaking of the Ford grant, Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior advisor for economic development, provided insight into the overall importance of ITP to the continued strength of the Illinois business community.  "The Edgar Administration is committed to investing in a highly-trained workforce," Kustra said.  "Production of the redesigned Ford Taurus and Mercury Sable vehicles at the Chicago Assembly Plant, and so many key pieces at the Chicago Stamping Plant, required the installation of significant new technology.  Stringent export standards also contribute to Ford's need to consistently upgrade the skills of its own employees and those of its suppliers.  I am pleased we can assist Ford in helping workers meet this challenge." <p>
 
<center>###</center>

<h3>TOP 10 TIPS FOR WRITING SUCCESSFUL CDAP APPLICATIONS</h3>

The Public Facilities component of DCCA's Community Development Assistance Program (CDAP) is one of the most important tools to help smaller Illinois communities address infrastructure needs that pose potential threats to public health and safety.  Public Facilities grants are just one component of CDAP, a federally-funded program administered by DCCA's Bureau of Community Development, that provides grants to local units of government in communities with populations of 50,000 or less that are not located within one of the seven large urban counties that receive funds directly from the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD).  But since CDAP Public Facilities grants are awarded on a competitive basis, it is crucial that communities submit the best possible application.  DCCA staffers often participate in workshops and seminars to help grantwriters refine their skills.  The following is a Top 10 List of their tips to help communities prepare more competitive applications:<p>

1.  Give your grantwriter sufficient time to prepare your CDAP application.  CDAP is a federally-funded program with complex requirements.  Make sure your grantwriter has enough time to thoroughly research and document the information in the application.<p>

2.  Know what you're sending.  Many communities hire grantwriters to prepare their applications, but ultimately the local government submitting the application is responsible for its contents and completeness.  For example, if other leverage is part of the project, be sure that leverage is in place before seeking the CDAP grant.  If it is not, your application will not be favorably reviewed.<p>

3.  At least 51 percent of the benefit from CDAP Public Facilities projects must be provided to low- and moderate-income (LMI) people.  Make sure the LMI documentation matches the actual project benefit area.  For example, if only a particular neighborhood of a community will be served by a project, income surveys or census data should only reflect that area, not the entire community.<p>

4.  Write a complete project summary narrative.  If you are proposing to extend water mains to serve a rural area, for example, include specific information about the condition of the private wells that are inadequately serving the area.  Survey the residents of the area -- are 20 of the 25 currently trucking in water or purchasing bottled water?  Include information about the age of an old city system that needs to be replaced.  How many breaks has it experienced in the past two years?  Does your community need a new water tower?  If so, include information about average daily water use or low water pressure and its effects on residents.<p>  

5.  Include a Project Location Map.  It doesn't have to be blueprint quality; it just needs to illustrate the entire project area and show the proposed improvements.<p>

6.  Document the existing threat to public health and safety.  Include "internal" reports, such as repair bills, citizen complaint records or letters, water quality test results, numbers of boil orders, data on breaks, engineering reports, as well as "external" documents, such as historical correspondence from the IEPA, or letters from the health department referencing test results and inspection results of the targeted area.<p> 

7.  Demonstrate financial need.  Why does your community need a grant?  What is your financial indebtedness?  Do you have bonding capacity?  What are current user rates for water and sewer services; could they be raised?  You must submit a copy of your most recent government audit with your CDAP application.  Be sure that if you have incurred additional debt since that audit was prepared, you inform us of that debt. (DCCA's Office of Local Government Services can conduct a financial analysis to help communities determine whether they need CDAP assistance.)<p>

8.  Demonstrate community effort.  What efforts has your community made to address the problem on its own?  Have you continually made repairs to an antiquated water treatment facility?  Have you exhausted local resources making sewer main repairs?  Have you contacted other funding sources, such as RECDS (FmHA), the Rural Bond Bank, the IEPA or local financial institutions?  If you have, and you've been turned down for help, indicate that in your application.  This tells us that you have taken the initiative and CDAP may be your only option.<p>

9.  Document project readiness.  CDAP guidelines now state that project readiness is a "project threshold."  In other words, if your application does not demonstrate that the proposed project is complete, appropriate and achievable, we may not review it further.  Be sure you review all of the project readiness guidelines and address them in your narrative:  a Preliminary Engineering Report that breaks down the project and its costs in detail; properly executed Agreements and Assurances, such as intergovernmental cooperation agreements; Firm Financial Commitments -- according to new CDAP guidelines, a minimum of 25 percent leverage must be "firmly" committed and documented according to the guidelines in the CDAP application; and Site Control, such as a signed commitment from a property owner for an easement or parcel of land and copies of any permits needed.<p>

10.  Document past CDAP performance, informing us of your timely and efficient completion of any past CDAP projects.  If your community experienced problems completing a past project on time, document circumstances beyond your control which might have delayed the project.<p> 

Every year, DCCA receives applications requesting nearly two times more in CDAP Public Facilities grants than funds available.  A complete, detailed application can increase your community's chances of success.  For further information, contact the CDAP staff at 217/785-6142 (TDD users call 800/785-6055.)<p>

<center>###</center>
<p>

Gov. Jim Edgar recently presented a check for $325,000 to Mayor Dorothy Mansholt of Litchfield.  The community is one of 31 that recently shared $7 million in Community Development Assistance Program (CDAP) housing grants to assist in their efforts to renovate substandard housing.<p>

<center>###</center>

<h3>DCCA, REGIONAL PARTNERS, REPRESENT ILLINOIS AT SAE '96</h3>
<h4>by GeorgeAnn Madison, DCCA Bureau of Business Development</h4>
	
This year's Society of Automotive Engineers (SAE) Exposition, held last month in Detroit, celebrated an important milestone:  the 100th Year Anniversary of the automotive industry.   Illinois, among the nation's leading automotive industry locations, was well-represented at the show through a booth manned by DCCA's local economic development partners and sponsored by DCCA's  Regional Economic Development Partnership Program (REDPP).<p>

REDPP provides funds that enable local and regional economic development professionals to attend various in-state and out-of-state trade shows to promote their communities and Illinois.  SAE '96 was one example of the kinds of expositions that are targeted for REDPP funding -- expositions that reach top prospects, both national and international, from Illinois' most important industries.<p>

Recognized worldwide as the leading exposition supporting a network of the automotive industry's top executives, engineers and company representatives, the SAE International Exposition is the oldest assembly of high-level industry personnel and suppliers and holds the honor of being the industry's largest and most prestigious automotive event.  Each year this event draws 850-plus supplier exhibits and includes more than 100 companies from outside North America showing their wares to an audience of more than 40,000 engineering professionals including 3,200 from overseas.<p>

A highlight of the Illinois booth was a Mitsubishi Eclipse convertible donated for the exhibit by Mitsubishi Motors Manufacturing of America, Inc., Normal.   The flashy auto helped attract attendees to the Illinois booth, where they were able to meet one-on-one with economic development personnel.  The contacts are important for both sides -- they enable industry professionals to learn about Illinois and offer Illinois economic developers an excellent opportunity to develop a list of qualified industry contacts and meet with industry decision-makers.<p>

SAE '96 also showcased another feature of REDPP.  The program enables participants to use portions of their funding for pre-show promotional efforts.  Illinois' exhibit, for example, was featured in a pre-show issue of Automotive Engineering (an organized pre-show promotional manual), as well as the Exhibitor's Manual (an on-site show directory).  These advertising efforts also had a two-pronged benefit -- they encouraged exhibitors to visit the Illinois booth, while providing Illinois exhibitors with access to a mailing list of all registered attendees at the SAE'96 Expo for future contact.<p>

DCCA and its local and regional partners will follow through on the leads they received at the SAE '96 Expo by mailing letters to contacts, providing an overview of Illinois' resources and attributes.   It's just one example of ways DCCA is working with local economic developers to attract and retain key industries and their jobs.<p>
<center>
</center>###

<h3>ILLINOIS TO HOST AFFORDABLE COMFORT CONFERENCE</h3>
<h4>by Henry Kurth, Bureau of Energy and Recycling</h4>

DCCA's  Bureau of Energy and Recycling, in cooperation with Affordable Comfort, Inc., are leading sponsors of the 10th Annual Affordable Comfort Conference, coming up March 17 through March 22 at the Palmer House Hotel in Chicago.<p>

The conference is designed to bolster the skills and knowledge of people who work on solutions to energy and housing problems, including problems faced by low-income households.  It features information on unique and cutting-edge technologies to help architects, builders, developers and other housing officials improve the energy efficiency of new and existing housing stock.<p>

The six-day conference will feature workshops, half- and full-day short courses, an energy exhibit area, participant-initiated sessions, special evening technical sessions, and an architect's forum.  Fourteen different technical tracks are featured, including Resource Efficient Construction, HVAC Systems, Marketing Comfort and Efficiency, and Energy Efficient Mortgages.  In addition, 90 different sessions conducted by some of the world's leading energy professionals will enable participants to choose workshops that meet their specific needs.  The Conference also will feature short courses with hands-on and in-field training, and an energy exhibit by more than 40 energy product, service, and equipment vendors.<p>

This is the first year that the Affordable Comfort Conference has been held in Illinois.  Chicago was chosen following a review of prospective sites by the Affordable Comfort Board, which selected the proposal submitted by the Bureau of Energy and Recycling with support from Gov. Jim Edgar.  The 1997 conference also will be held in Chicago.<p>

For more information or a conference brochure, contact Maureen Davlin or Chrissie Garrison of DCCA's Bureau of Energy and Recyclinvg at 217/785-2800 (TDD users call 217/785-0211).<p>

<center>###</center>

<h3>ENERGY ASSISTANCE HOTLINE CAN BE A LIFELINE</h3>
<h4>by Curt Farrar, DCCA Division of Economic Opportunity</h4>

To some, handling more than 40,000 calls annually on DCCA's Energy Assistance Hotline would seem a tedious job.  But to the staff of the  Division of Economic Opportunity, particularly Support Services staffers, Esther Reed, John Ray, and Jan Stehlin, it's an important and rewarding service.<p>

The Energy Assistance Hotline is an information and referral source for those individuals seeking assistance with their heating bills, home weatherization, and other emergency services offered through the Illinois Home Weatherization Assistance, Low-Income Home Energy Assistance, and Community Services Block Grant Programs.<p>

Established in 1979 near the same time as DCCA's creation, the Hotline started as two phones with headsets installed in a separate room at the Department's offices. Then as now, staffers took calls from individuals wanting to know what the energy assistance and weatherization programs were all about, program eligibility requirements, and information on where they could apply.<p>

Although some people call to express complaints, Reed says, "The rewards come when you can help people such as Mr. Jenkins who writes, "My blood level is monitored weekly being on blood thinner. I get cold. I am 60 years old...Right leg amputee up to hip...I am wheelchair bound. Please help." <p>

Besides answering questions about DCCA's programs, Hotline staffers also retain a listing of other agencies' toll-free numbers, including those of Public Aid, Mental Health, Aging, and the Department of Children and Family Services.  Well-established communication channels also are maintained with the state's electric and gas utilities, including Commonwealth Edison, People's Gas, CILCO, and Illinois Power.<p>

Reed is proud of the work she and other DCCA staffers do.  "We're a small operation with only one phone line, but we probably touch every segment of the state's social services network.  We are a lifeline for a lot of needy people across the state."<p>

The Energy Assistance Hotline number is 800/252-8643 (TDD users call 800/785-6055).<p>

<center>###</center>


Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra recently convened a "Coal Strategy Group" of leaders from the Illinois Coal Association, United Mine Workers of America and state agencies, including DCCA.  The group will discuss ways to improve the economic viability of Illinois coal thus ensuring a positive impact on local communities.<p>

<center>###</center>
<p>
<strong><em>DCCA NEWS</em></strong> is published monthly by the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs.  Dennis R. Whetstone, Director.  Direct all correspondence to Lynn Morford, Editor, 620 E. Adams Street, Sixth Floor, Springfield, Illinois 62701 (or e-mail at lynn.morford@accessil.com).<p>

